## Front Matter & Book Structure

### Publication Details
- Full title: *The Rise and Fall of the Great Powers: Economic Change and
  Military Conflict from 1500 to 2000*
- Author: **Paul Kennedy**
- Publisher: Vintage Books (Random House), First Vintage edition January 1989
- Originally published in hardcover 1987
- Written at Hamden, Connecticut, 1986

### Book Structure (Table of Contents)
Three major parts:

**Part I: Strategy and Economics in the Preindustrial World**
- Ch 1: The Rise of the Western World
  (Ming China / Muslim World / Japan & Russia / "The European Miracle")
- Ch 2: The Habsburg Bid for Mastery, 1519–1659
  (Strengths & Weaknesses of Habsburg Bloc / War, Money, Nation-State)
- Ch 3: Finance, Geography, and the Winning of Wars, 1660–1815
  (The "Financial Revolution" / Geopolitics / Winning of Wars 1660–1815)

**Part II: Strategy and Economics in the Industrial Era**
- Ch 4: Industrialization and the Shifting Global Balances, 1815–1885
  (Eclipse of Non-European World / Britain as Hegemon? / Middle Powers /
  Crimean War / U.S. Civil War / Wars of German Unification)
- Ch 5: The Coming of a Bipolar World, Part One, 1885–1918
  (Shifting Balance of World Forces / Alliances and Drift to War / Total War)
- Ch 6: The Coming of a Bipolar World, Part Two, 1919–1942
  (Postwar International Order / The Challengers / Offstage Superpowers /
  Unfolding Crisis 1931–1942)

**Part III: Strategy and Economics Today and Tomorrow**
- Ch 7: Stability and Change in a Bipolar World, 1943–1980
  ("Proper Application of Overwhelming Force" / New Strategic Landscape /
  Cold War and the Third World / Fissuring of Bipolar World /
  Changing Economic Balances 1950–1980)
- Ch 8: To the Twenty-first Century
  (China's Balancing Act / The Japanese Dilemma / EEC—Potential and Problems /
  Soviet Union and Its "Contradictions" /
  **The United States: The Problem of Number One in Relative Decline**)

### Analytical Framework: Tables & Charts (49 statistical tables)
The sheer density of quantitative data Kennedy marshals signals his method:
- Military manpower increases (1470–1660)
- British wartime expenditure and revenue (1688–1815)
- Populations, army sizes, navy sizes across the powers
- **Relative shares of world manufacturing output** (1750–1900, 1880–1938,
  1929–1938) — the book's central recurring metric
- **Per capita levels of industrialization** (1750–1900, 1880–1938)
- GNP, per capita GNP, national income of powers at key dates
- Iron/steel production, energy consumption, armaments output
- Defense expenditures as % of national income
- Nuclear warheads, worldwide U.S. force deployments (1987)
- U.S. federal deficit, debt, and interest (1980–1985)

> These tables are not decoration — they are the argument.
> Relative manufacturing share and industrialization levels are
> the core evidence for rise and fall.

---

## Introduction (begins p. 19)

### Core Subject and Scope
- Book traces how **Great Powers** have risen and fallen *relative to each
  other* over five centuries — from formation of "new monarchies" of
  western Europe and beginnings of the transoceanic global state system
- Heavily concerned with wars, especially major **drawn-out conflicts
  fought by coalitions of Great Powers** — those with outsized impact on
  international order
- But NOT a military history book; also NOT an economic history book —
  it occupies the intersection

> "What it concentrates upon is the *interaction* between economics and
> strategy, as each of the leading states in the international system
> strove to enhance its wealth and its power, to become (or to remain)
> both rich and strong."

### The Central Argument (stated in Introduction, elaborated in text)
The triumph or collapse of any Great Power has been the consequence of
**three interacting factors**:
1. Lengthy fighting by armed forces
2. **Efficient utilization of the state's productive economic resources
   in wartime**
3. The way the state's economy had been rising or falling **relative to
   other leading nations in the decades preceding the actual conflict**

Key implication: **peacetime economic trajectory matters as much as
wartime military performance**

> "How a Great Power's position steadily alters in peacetime is as
> important to this study as how it fights in wartime."

### Military Conflict Always Examined in Economic Context
- "Military conflict" in the subtitle is always examined in context of
  "economic change"
- Not just battlefield outcomes — the prior, structural economic
  position determines the outcome before the war begins
- This makes the book prospective as well as historical:
  you can read current economic trends as signals of future power shifts

### Methodological Note
- Kennedy explicitly acknowledges "cultural assumptions" may have
  emerged in the first two chapters — colleague **Jonathan Spence**
  tried to curb these
- **John Elliott** reviewed Ch 2 (Habsburg chapter)
- **Paddy O'Brien** and **John Bosher** consulted on 18th-century
  British and French finance
- **Nick Rizopoulos** and **Michael Mandelbaum** reviewed later chapters;
  presentations at the **Lehrman Institute** in New York
- Editor: **Jason Epstein** (Random House) — repeatedly pushed Kennedy
  to think of the general reader
- Research assistance from Kevin Smith (historical statistics),
  libraries at University of East Anglia and Yale

---

## Notes on What to Watch For (from ToC structure)
- The Habsburg chapter is the first major case study — Spain's failure
  to translate territorial dominance into lasting hegemony
- The "Financial Revolution" section in Ch 3 will be key —
  Britain's ability to fund wars through debt distinguished it
- The question mark after "Britain as Hegemon?" in Ch 4 signals
  Kennedy is skeptical of simple hegemonic narratives
- Ch 8's final section — "The United States: The Problem of Number One
  in Relative Decline" — is what made the book controversial in 1987,
  predicting American **imperial overstretch**
- The 49 statistical tables are the empirical backbone;
  manufacturing share and industrialization levels are the
  two key recurring metrics throughout


<!-- pp. 21-40 -->

## Introduction (continued): The Book's Thesis and Chapter Road Map

### Core Argument: Wealth-Power Nexus

- **Uneven growth rates** among nations are the primary driver of shifting
  power balances — technological and organizational breakthroughs benefit
  some states far more than others
- Example: the **long-range gunned sailing ship** and Atlantic trade after
  1500 were not uniformly beneficial — some nations gained far more
- **Circular relationship:** wealth underwrites military power; military
  power acquires and protects wealth
- **The dilemma:** if too large a share of state resources is diverted to
  military purposes, national power weakens over the longer term
- **Strategic overextension** — conquering extensive territories or waging
  costly wars — risks outweighing the benefits of expansion, especially
  during economic decline
- Key correlation: over the long term, productive and revenue-raising
  capacity tracks closely with military strength

### Chapter-by-Chapter Overview (Kennedy's Road Map)

- **Chapter 1** — World around 1500: Ming China, Ottoman Empire, Mughal
  India, Muscovy, Tokugawa Japan, and western European states. Western
  Europe's rise was not inevitable.
- **Chapter 2** — The **Habsburg bid for mastery** (~1500–1660): Spain
  and Austria repeatedly overextended militarily for a weakening economic
  base; rivals maintained a better balance between resources and force
- **Chapter 3** (1660–1815) — Not one dominant bloc vs. rivals, but five
  major states emerging: **France, Britain, Russia, Austria, Prussia**.
  France under **Louis XIV** and **Napoleon** came closest to hegemony
  but was always checked by coalitions. Britain's advanced banking/credit
  system and geographical position as a "flank" nation gave it lasting
  advantages. Industrial Revolution underway in Britain by late 18th c.
- **Chapter 4** (post-1815) — **Concert of Europe** brings strategic
  equilibrium; no bid for dominance. Britain rises to zenith as global
  naval/colonial/commercial power, backed by monopoly on steam-driven
  industry. By 1880s, industrialization spreads and tilts balances away
  from older powers.
- **Chapters 5 & 6** — Transition to **bipolar world**: U.S. and Russia
  emerge as continental giants. Traditional European powers (France,
  Austria-Hungary, Italy) fall behind. Germany alone among western
  Europeans might force its way into the top league. Japan ascendant in
  East Asia only.
  - WWI: Germany won in the east but lost in the west when U.S. resources
    entered. By 1918, the **United States** was indisputably the
    strongest Power in the world.
  - Post-1919: U.S. withdrawal + Soviet isolationism left international
    system "more out of joint with fundamental economic realities than
    perhaps at any time in the five centuries." Revisionist middle
    Powers (Italy, Japan, Germany) had to expand or be overshadowed.
  - WWII confirmed: **Axis could not overcome the productive resource
    imbalance** against the Allied coalition. By 1943 the bipolar world
    forecast decades earlier had arrived.
- **Chapters 7–8** — Cold War bipolarity: U.S. and USSR in class of
  their own, reinforced by nuclear weapons. But the rise-and-fall process
  never ceased:
  - U.S.-USSR arms race escalates while their global production shares
    **shrink**
  - EEC becomes world's largest trading unit; Japan overtakes USSR in GNP
  - China "leaping forward at an impressive rate"
  - **Multipolar world already exists economically** even if military
    balances lag — the disjuncture between productive and military
    balances is the book's contemporary problem

### Methodological Notes (What the Book Is NOT)

- Not about **Kondratieff cycles** linking major wars to economic
  up/downturns
- Not a general theory of the **causes of war** (rising vs. falling
  powers triggering conflict)
- Not a theory of **empire** or whether imperial control pays
  (cf. **Michael Doyle**, *Empires*)
- Not economic determinism — geography, military organization, national
  morale, alliances all matter
  - 18th century: Dutch (richest in Europe) fell; Russia (poorest) rose
  - Individual folly (Hitler) and battlefield competence (Spanish
    tercios, German infantry) explain individual outcomes

### Key Generalizations Kennedy Does Draw

- **Productive balances → power balances** (with lag): shifts in trade
  flows (Mediterranean → Atlantic after 1500; manufacturing shares away
  from western Europe after 1890) heralded rise of new Great Powers
- **Lag time** between economic and military trajectories: an expanding
  power prefers growth over armaments; a half-century later it has
  accumulated overseas obligations and faces rising rivals — defense
  spending rises even as relative position weakens
- **Great Powers in relative decline instinctively spend more on
  security**, diverting resources from investment — compounding the
  long-term dilemma (Spain in 1630s–40s; Britain in 1910; U.S. and USSR
  today at time of writing)
- **Coalition wars are won by the side with more productive resources:**
  true of wars against Habsburgs, 18th-century contests (War of Spanish
  Succession, Seven Years' War, Napoleonic Wars), and both World Wars

> "whether a nation be today mighty and rich or not depends not on the
> abundance or security of its power and riches, but principally on
> whether its neighbors possess more or less of it."
> — **von Hornigk**, German mercantilist, cited by Kennedy

- **Relative, not absolute:** Netherlands in mid-18th century was richer
  in absolute terms than a century earlier, yet much less of a Great
  Power because France and Britain had grown more. Britain today has
  far greater wealth than in its Victorian prime — yet its share of world
  product shrank from ~25% to ~3%.

### Intellectual Lineage

- Book modeled on **Leopold von Ranke**'s 1833 essay *die grossen Mächte*
  ("the great powers") — surveyed power balance shifts since Spain's
  decline, examined prospects of contemporary Great Powers
- Kennedy originally intended a brief "essayistic" book; reader demand
  for detail led to full historical treatment, filling a gap neither
  economic historians nor military historians had entered

---

## Part One: Strategy & Economics in the Preindustrial World

## Chapter 1: The Rise of the Western World

### Europe in 1500 — Apparently Weak

- **1500** chosen by scholars as the modern/premodern divide — but to
  contemporaries it was NOT obvious Europe was poised to dominate
- Eastern empires appeared far more impressive: enormous wealth, vast
  armies, advanced civilizations
- Europe's weaknesses in 1500:
  - Not the most fertile or populous region (India and China led)
  - Geopolitically awkward shape: open to landward invasion from east
  - Fall of **Constantinople (1453)** still fresh — shock to Christendom
  - **Ottoman Turks** had taken Greece, Ionian Islands, Bosnia, Albania,
    Balkans; janissary armies pressed toward Budapest and Vienna by 1520s
  - **Sultan Mehmet II** directed coherent grand strategy; European
    response was disjointed and sporadic
- Europe was "a hodgepodge of petty kingdoms and principalities, marcher
  lordships and city-states" — no unified authority

### Why Europe's Fragmentation Was an Advantage

- All other great civilizations suffered from **centralized authority**
  that enforced uniformity in religion, commerce, and weapons development
- Europe's lack of supreme authority + warlike rivalries among states
  created **constant pressure for military innovation**
- This competitive, entrepreneurial environment interacted fruitfully with
  technological and commercial advances
- Result: a "constantly upward spiral of economic growth and enhanced
  military effectiveness" — carrying Europe ahead of all other regions

### The State of Civilizations ~1500 (Rough Parity)

- All great centers (Ming China, Ottoman Empire, Mughal India, Muscovy,
  western Europe) at roughly similar development stages — each more
  advanced in some areas, less in others
- Much of European cultural/scientific heritage "borrowed" from Islam,
  which had borrowed from China
- Europe accelerating commercially and technologically by late 15th
  century, but rise was not predetermined

---

### Ming China

### China's Extraordinary Strengths

- Most advanced civilization of premodern times — felt most superior
- **Population:** 100–130 million vs. Europe's 50–55 million (15th c.)
- Unified, hierarchic **Confucian bureaucracy** gave coherence and
  sophistication envied by foreign visitors
- Survived Mongol domination (Kublai Khan); the **Ming dynasty** (1368)
  reunited empire — "China had a habit of changing its conquerors more
  than it was changed by them"

### Technological Precocity

- **Movable type printing** in 11th-century China; huge libraries
- **Paper money** expedited commerce and market growth
- **Magnetic compass** — a Chinese invention
- **Gunpowder** — Chinese probably first true inventors; Ming used
  cannons to overthrow Mongol rulers (late 14th century)
- **Iron industry:** north China produced ~125,000 tons/year in the
  11th century — **far larger than British iron output in the early
  Industrial Revolution, seven centuries later**
- Cities far larger than medieval European equivalents; trade routes
  as extensive

### Ming Naval Power

- **1420 Ming navy:** 1,350 combat vessels including 400 large floating
  fortresses and 250 long-range cruising ships — dwarfing European
  navies of the era
- **Admiral Cheng Ho** — seven long-distance expeditions, 1405–1433,
  with hundreds of ships and tens of thousands of men
  - Reached Malacca, Ceylon, Red Sea, Zanzibar
  - Treasure ships ~400 feet long, displacing 1,500+ tons (vs.
    Portuguese caravels)
  - Could theoretically have sailed around Africa and "discovered"
    Portugal decades before **Henry the Navigator** pushed south of Ceuta
  - Notably: "the Chinese apparently never plundered nor murdered —
    unlike the Portuguese, Dutch, and other European invaders"

### China's Deliberate Retreat

- **1433:** Last Cheng Ho expedition
- **1436:** Imperial edict banned construction of seagoing ships
- Later: specific order forbade ships with more than two masts
- Naval personnel reassigned to smaller canal vessels; Cheng Ho's
  great warships rotted away
- **Plausible strategic rationale:** Mongol pressure on northern
  frontier made large navy an expensive luxury; expansion into Annam
  (Vietnam) costly and fruitless
- But: the decision was **never reconsidered** even when Japanese
  pirates attacked Chinese coastline, or when Portuguese vessels
  appeared off China — "Defense on land was all that was required"

### The Confucian Bureaucracy as Brake on Growth

- Key driver of retreat: **conservatism of the Confucian bureaucracy**,
  heightened in Ming period by resentment at Mongol-forced changes
- In the "Restoration" atmosphere, officialdom sought to preserve the
  past, not build a commercial future
- Confucian code: warfare deplorable; armed forces only for barbarian
  threats
- **Mandarins distrusted merchants:** accumulation of private capital,
  buying cheap/selling dear, ostentation of the nouveau riche all
  offended the scholarly elite
- Mandarins routinely confiscated merchant property or banned their
  businesses; foreign trade especially suspicious (less controllable)
- State-driven technology could be started AND stopped by bureaucratic
  decree:
  - Canals permitted to decay
  - Army periodically starved of equipment
  - Astronomical clocks (built c. 1090) disregarded
  - Ironworks gradually fell into disuse
  - **Printing restricted to scholarly works** — not used for practical
    knowledge or social criticism
  - Paper currency discontinued
- Chinese cities never had the autonomy of Western cities — no Chinese
  burgher class; when emperor's court moved, the capital city moved too
- Merchants who acquired wealth tended to invest in land and education,
  not proto-industrial development
- Foreign trade with Portuguese and Dutch (later centuries) was in
  luxury goods, controlled by officials

### China's Relative Decline

- Ming China far less vigorous than under the **Sung dynasty**, four
  centuries earlier
- Agricultural improvements eventually could not keep pace with
  population growth; **Malthusian checks** (plague, floods, war) were
  the only limit
- Even the replacement of Mings by the more vigorous **Manchus** (1644)
  could not halt the relative decline

> In 1736 — just as **Abraham Darby**'s ironworks at Coalbrookdale were
> beginning to boom — the blast furnaces and coke ovens of Honan and
> Hopei were abandoned entirely. They had been great before the Conqueror
> landed at Hastings. Now they would not resume production until the
> twentieth century.

<!-- pp. 41-60 -->

## The Muslim World

### Ottoman Empire — Rise
- In the 16th century, Muslim states were the most rapidly expanding forces in world affairs
- **Safavid Persia** resurging under **Ismail I** (1500–1524) and **Abbas I** (1587–1629)
- Muslim khanates controlled Silk Road; Hindu empire in Java overthrown; **Babur** established **Mughal Empire** in 1526
- **Akbar** (1556–1605) consolidated Mughal control from Baluchistan to Bengal
- Muslim proselytization in Africa and the Indies vastly outpaced Christian missions

### Ottoman Military Power
- Greatest Muslim challenge to Europe: **Ottoman Turks** — finest siege train of the age
- By 1500s, domains stretched from Crimea to the Levant; seized Damascus 1516, Egypt 1517
  - Used Turkish cannon to shatter Mamluk forces; closed spice route from the Indies
- **Suleiman** (1520–1566) resumed European push; Hungary overrun after **Battle of Mohacs** (1526)
- By 1529, Turks besieging Vienna — line stabilized in northern Hungary but threat persisted until 1683
- Ottoman naval expansion: navy built to take **Constantinople** (1453), then used across Black Sea, Aegean
  - Seized Cyprus 1570–71; checked only at **Battle of Lepanto**

### Ottoman Empire — Strengths
- More than a military machine: unified official faith, culture, and language over an area exceeding Rome
- Islam had been culturally and technologically ahead of Europe for centuries before 1500
  - Advanced in mathematics, cartography, medicine, mills, gun-casting, horsebreeding
- **Janissary** system: recruited from Christian youth in the Balkans — dedicated, uniform corps
- Tolerance of other races drew talent: a Hungarian was **Mehmet's** chief gun-caster at Constantinople
- Under **Suleiman I**: bureaucracy of 14 million subjects; Constantinople had 500,000 inhabitants by 1600

### Ottoman Decline
- **Strategic overextension** by the second half of the 16th century:
  - Large army in central Europe, navy in Mediterranean, troops in North Africa + Aegean + Crimea
- **Shi'ite/Sunni split**: Persia under **Abbas the Great** allied with European states against Ottomans
  - Persia's willingness to ally with "infidels" directly mirrors France working with Ottomans vs. Habsburgs
- After 1566: thirteen incompetent sultans in succession
- Systemic failures (like Ming China): centralized, despotic, orthodox — hostile to initiative and commerce
  - "An idiot sultan could paralyze the Ottoman Empire in the way that a pope or Holy Roman Emperor could never do for all Europe"
- Without territorial expansion and booty after 1550: janissaries turned to internal plunder
- Merchants (nearly all foreigners) subjected to unpredictable taxes and property seizure
- **Printing press forbidden** — could disseminate dangerous opinions
- Guilds supported to check innovation; imports desired but exports forbidden
- In 1580, janissaries **destroyed a state observatory** alleging it had caused a plague
- After Lepanto, did not build larger European-style vessels; Muslim fleets ordered to stay in calmer Red Sea/Persian Gulf waters
- Janissaries slow to replace bulky cannon with lighter cast-iron guns — cultural conservatism trumped military logic

### Mughal Empire
- Despite brilliant courts, sophisticated banking/credit, and Hindu merchant entrepreneurialism, the system was weak at the core
- Muslim elite atop vast poverty-stricken peasant Hindu majority
- Hindu religious taboos (no killing rodents/insects → food loss; caste → throttled initiative; Brahman priests → obscurantism at highest level) militated against modernization
- Mogul rule was a **systematic plunder machine**: tax collectors preyed on peasants regardless of harvest; taxation known as "eating"
  - Population received nothing in return — no famine relief, no infrastructure
- "All this makes the Ming dynasty appear benign, almost progressive, by comparison"
- Decline officially caused by Marathas, Afghans, East India Company — but internal causes were primary

---

## Two Outsiders — Japan and Russia

### Japan
- 16th century: feudal clan-based power; emperor was a cipher; constant inter-clan feuding (compared to Scottish clan strife)
- Geography gave Japan insularity — protection from overland invasion China lacked
- More open than Ming China: Japanese pirates raided Chinese/Korean coasts while other Japanese traded with Portuguese and Dutch; Christian missions penetrated far more easily than into Ming China
- Firearms concentrated power: warlord **Hideyoshi** used imported European armaments to consolidate control; attempted to conquer Korea twice; died 1598
- **Tokugawa** clan completed consolidation; **Ieyasu** established shogunate that could not be shaken

### Tokugawa Isolation
- 1636: construction of oceangoing vessels stopped; Japanese forbidden to sail high seas
- Trade with Europeans restricted to **one Dutch ship** at Deshima, Nagasaki; all Christians (foreign and native) murdered
- Motive: **Tokugawa determination for unchallenged control** — foreigners, Christians, and feudal rivals all seen as subversive
- Feudal lords required to spend half the year in the capital; families held at Yedo (Tokyo) as virtual hostages
- Result: merchants and bankers grew more important economically but were **never permitted social/political prominence** as in Italy, Netherlands, and Britain
- Military system ossified for two centuries — when **Commodore Perry's** "black ships" arrived in 1853, Japan could only acquiesce

### Russia
- **Kingdom of Muscovy** geographically isolated, but deeply influenced by European inheritance (especially Russian Orthodox Church)
- Western muskets and cannon solved Russia's vulnerability to Asian horsemen — enabled "gunpowder empire" expansion
  - By 1556, Russian troops reached the Caspian Sea; by 1638, explorers had reached the Pacific coast
- Westward expansion blocked by Swedes and Poles who also possessed firearms
- Persistent vulnerabilities: **Tartar khanate of the Crimea** sacked Moscow in 1571; Poles occupied Moscow 1608–1613
- **Ivan the Terrible** purged restive nobles but systemic weaknesses remained:
  - Military absolutism of the czars; education monopolized by the Orthodox Church; serfdom; unpredictable bureaucracy
- Russia borrowed enough from Europe to maintain military strength but firmly resisted western social and political modernization
  - Foreigners in Russia **segregated** from natives to prevent subversive influences
- Unlike Ming, Ottoman, Mughal empires, czarist Russia would survive and eventually become a world power — but in 1500–1650, few western Europeans knew more about Russian rulers than they did about the legendary **Prester John**

---

## The "European Miracle"

### The Central Question
- Why did the scattered, relatively unsophisticated peoples of western Eurasia generate unstoppable economic and technological development to become global commercial and military leaders?
- Kennedy's thesis: there was a **dynamic** driven chiefly by economic and technological advances, interacting with social structure, geography, and occasional accident
- Power is **relative** — must be measured by comparing states and societies, not in isolation

### Geography as Foundation
- Europe's most striking feature to any observer of world power centers in the 16th century: **political fragmentation**
  - Not accidental — Europe had *always* been politically fragmented; even Rome failed to conquer much beyond Rhine and Danube
- Geography drove this: no enormous plains for horsemen to impose dominion; no great river valleys creating masses of easily-conquerable peasants
  - Fractured landscape of mountain ranges and forests separated population centers
- Result: decentralized power — local kingdoms, marcher lordships, highland clans, lowland town confederations
- Differentiated climate → differentiated products → **bulk trade** (timber, grain, wine, wool, herrings) not luxury caravans
- Many navigable rivers + surrounding seas → flourishing maritime commerce Baltic–North Sea–Mediterranean
- Long-distance trade led to bills of exchange, credit, and international banking — a basic **predictability of economic conditions** private traders had rarely enjoyed anywhere in the world

### Political Pluralism as Economic Engine
- No uniform authority in Europe could suppress commercial development — no central government to ban industries
- Contrast with Mogul India: no "systematic and universal plundering of businessmen and entrepreneurs by tax gatherers"
- Example: "it was inconceivable in Reformation Europe that everyone would acknowledge the pope's 1494 division of the overseas world into Spanish and Portuguese spheres"
- Persecution of merchants (Jewish traders, Flemish textile workers, Huguenots) backfired: they moved and took their expertise elsewhere
  - A Rhineland baron who overtaxed travelers found trade routes went elsewhere, taking his revenues with them
  - A monarch who repudiated debts found it nearly impossible to raise loans when war threatened
- Gradually, European regimes entered a **symbiotic relationship** with market economy: providing domestic order and non-arbitrary legal systems in exchange for tax revenue
  - Adam Smith's formula anticipated in practice: "peace, easy taxes, and tolerable administration of justice"

### Why No European Gunpowder Empire?
- Firearms technology concentrated power elsewhere (Muscovy, Tokugawa Japan, Mughal India) — why not Europe?
- Each European rival state **could access** the same military techniques — no single power held a decisive edge
  - Swiss mercenaries available to any bidder; cannon produced near ore deposits in Weald, Milan, Liège, Málaga, Sweden
  - Shipbuilding skills spread from Baltic to Black Sea — impossible for any one country to monopolize maritime power
- Key insight: it was not merely that competitors existed, but that *most of them possessed or could buy the military means to preserve their independence*

### The Arms Race Dynamic
- Political decentralization generated a **primitive arms race** among city-states then kingdoms
- Italian city-states' merchant-funded armies demanded **value for money** — they required swift victories, driving innovation
- Free-market system forced *condottieri* to compete for contracts and artisans to improve weapons to secure new orders
- Cannon initially no better in the West than in Asia — same massive wrought-iron tubes used at Constantinople (1453)
- Only in Europe did sustained competitive pressure drive **constant improvement**: better gunpowder grains, smaller bronze/tin alloys, improved barrel shapes, mobile gun carriages
  - French army equipped with formidable bronze guns invaded Italy in 1494 — Italian city-states panicked; **Leonardo da Vinci's** notebooks from this period contain designs for a machine gun, primitive tank, and steam-powered cannon
- In China, Japan, Mughal India: once cannon monopoly established authority, **incentive to improve vanished**
  - Janissaries of Islam scorned improving artillery until too late; Russian/Mogul commanders faced only less-advanced peoples, so existing weapons sufficed

### Counter-Fortification and Political Pluralism Preserved
- Within a quarter-century of the French invasion (1494): Italians discovered **raised earthworks inside city walls** could absorb cannonballs
- Sophisticated bastions with crossfire from muskets and cannon became near-insuperable to siege infantry
- Effect: restored security to city-states that had sufficient manpower; also helped Christian garrisons resist Turks (Malta, northern Hungary)
- Critical consequence: **prevented any single European power from achieving decisive conquest** — the gunpowder revolution that unified Japan and India was structurally blocked in Europe

### The Gunned Ship and Maritime Supremacy
- Around 1400–1450, Chinese (Cheng Ho voyages) and Turkish naval power might have seemed the future of maritime development
- What differed was **sustained organization** — Europe's ability to rationalize exploration and mobilize resources, not just reach distant places
- Portuguese systematic collection of geographical data; Genoese merchant houses funding Atlantic ventures; Newfoundland cod fisheries — all reflected a readiness to reach outward absent elsewhere
- Key innovation: **siting cannon on sailing vessels**
  - Bronze cannon were smaller, more powerful, less dangerous than wrought-iron bombards — predictable they'd go aboard ships
  - Stoutly built, round-hulled, all-weather **three-masted sailing vessel** had inherent advantage over slim oared galleys
  - Could fire larger broadside while remaining stable; once guns sited amidships (not on fore/aft castles) the *potential power* of caravels and galleons was formidable
- Evolution was slow — galley-type vessels still in English Channel in the 16th century; galleys remained superior for inshore Mediterranean operations
  - "As soon as the first Portuguese vessels rounded the Cape of Good Hope, the age of unchallenged western dominance had [not yet] begun"

<!-- pp. 61-80 -->

## Chapter 1 (continued): The European Miracle — Limits and Legacy

### Limits of Early European Expansion

- **Portugal's reach was precarious**: ships often only 300 tons; couldn't penetrate the
  Red Sea for long; lost some East African stations to an Arab counteroffensive by the
  late 16th century
- Non-European powers did NOT simply collapse at first contact:
  - **China** voluntarily abandoned maritime trade — the Portuguese trading post at
    **Macao** (1557) barely disturbed Peking's equanimity
  - **Japan** killed most members of a Portuguese diplomatic mission in 1640;
    Lisbon was in no position to retaliate
  - **Ottoman** sea power held its own in the eastern Mediterranean; loss of Hungary
    was *far more alarming* to European statesmen than gains in the Orient

> "To most European statesmen the loss of Hungary was of far greater import than the
> establishment of factories in the Orient, and the threat to Vienna more significant
> than their own challenges at Aden, Goa and Malacca."

### The Decisive Advantage: Artillery at Sea

- Portuguese tactic: "they were by no means to board, but to fight with the artillery"
  — made them virtually invincible at sea against Arab dhows and light craft
- On land a different story — fierce defeats at Aden, Jiddah, Goa — but still carved a
  chain of forts from Gulf of Guinea to South China Sea by mid-16th century
- Never monopolized the spice trade (Venice kept receiving supply via traditional
  routes), but cornered major portions and profited greatly

### The Spanish Land Empire

- Conquistadors moved from Hispaniola/Cuba → Mexico (1520s) → Peru (1530s);
  empire stretched River Plate to Rio Grande within decades
- **Potosí silver mine** (Peru): biggest single deposit in the world for over a century
- Transatlantic trade volume: **8x increase 1510–1550**, then **3x again 1550–1610**
- Unlike **Cheng Ho**'s fleeting voyages, Portuguese/Spanish built permanent structures
  (churches, administration, ranches, mines) — committed to altering the world's
  political and economic balances for good

### The "Modern World System" Emerges

- By mid-16th century, separate expansions were interlocking into a single system:
  Guinea gold + Peru silver → pay for Asian spices/silks; Russian furs/timber →
  buy English iron guns; Baltic grain → Mediterranean via Amsterdam
- Self-reinforcing loop: expansion → trade gains → more expansion; wars interrupted
  but colonizers rarely permanently withdrew
- **Competitive pressure**: Spain and Portugal could not hold their papally assigned
  monopoly; by the 1560s Dutch, French, and English vessels were in the Atlantic,
  quickened by the Revolt of the Netherlands and the decline of English cloth trade

### Science and Technology Feedback Loop

- Commercial and colonial rivalry drove **parallel knowledge explosion**:
  telescope, barometer, backstaff, gimbaled compass; improved cartography and
  navigation tables; deep-mining techniques; metallurgy; printing press disseminated
  findings broadly
- Cumulative effect: reinforced Europe's technological and military superiority further
- Even the Ottomans were feeling these consequences by end of the 16th century
- Contrarian point: whether Asian societies would have industrialized independently if
  left undisturbed is "open to considerable doubt" — the ladder was already full of
  European states occupying the top rungs

### The "European Miracle" — Root Causes

- Europe's advantage was structural, not just tactical: combination of:
  1. **Economic laissez-faire** — merchants and entrepreneurs not consistently
     preyed upon by despotic central authority
  2. **Political and military pluralism** — no single power could impose uniform
     orthodoxy; competitive stimulus was turbulent but productive
  3. **Intellectual liberty** — freedom to inquire, dispute, experiment; rationalism
     defied mandarin codes and religious dogma
- Key framing: "Europe's greatest advantage was that it had fewer *dis*advantages
  than the other civilizations"
- None of this mix existed in Ming China, the Ottoman Empire, or other societies
  examined — they appeared to stand still while Europe advanced

---

## Chapter 2: The Habsburg Bid for Mastery, 1519–1659

### Overview and Stakes

- By the 16th century, European power struggles were lifting the continent above other
  regions — but which European state would dominate the others remained open
- For ~150 years after 1500, the **Habsburg family** (Spanish + Austrian branches)
  threatened to become the predominant power in Europe
- By the **Treaty of the Pyrenees (1659)**, Spain finally acknowledged defeat;
  European *plurality* (5–6 major states) was confirmed as permanent

### The Meaning and Chronology of the Struggle

**Two root causes** of the intensified, continent-wide warfare after 1500:

1. **The Reformation** — **Martin Luther**'s revolt against papal indulgences (1517)
   fractured "Christendom" into a *transnational* religious struggle; divided Europe
   north/south and city middle classes vs. feudal orders; wars only grudgingly accepted
   as permanent by mid-17th century
2. **The Habsburg dynastic combination** — a network of territories from Gibraltar to
   Hungary, Sicily to Amsterdam; largest agglomeration since Charlemagne

### How the Habsburgs Assembled Their Empire

- **Maximilian I** (Austria, Holy Roman emperor 1508–1519):
  - married into Burgundy/Netherlands (1477)
  - marriage compact of 1515 added Hungary and Bohemia
  - son **Philip** married **Joan**, daughter of **Ferdinand and Isabella** of Spain
    (who had unified Castile and Aragon, including Naples and Sicily)
- **Charles V** (born 1500): inherited all four streams simultaneously
  - Duke of Burgundy at 15; **Charles I of Spain** 1516; Holy Roman emperor 1519
  - Added Hungary and Bohemia in 1526 when childless King Louis of Hungary
    died at the **Battle of Mohacs** against the Turks
  - Abdicated in 1555–1556, splitting the inheritance: Austrian branch to brother
    **Ferdinand I**; Spanish crown to son **Philip II**

> "Henceforth, like the doubleheaded black eagle in the imperial coat of arms, the
> Habsburgs had two heads at Vienna and at Madrid, looking east and west."
> — historian Mamatey

### Why Others Feared Habsburg Power

- **France (Valois kings)**: Habsburg territories seemed to encircle France entirely;
  breaking Habsburg influence became the chief French objective for two centuries
- **German princes**: alarmed that Charles V's outside resources might now let him
  impose his will inside Germany
- **Popes**: opposed Habsburg accumulation even when needing them against the Turks
- No conscious plan for "world monarchy" — marriages were fortuitous, not schemed;
  Habsburgs were often *reacting* (e.g., to French invasions of Italy)
- But: even their *defensive* goals, if achieved, would have effectively given them
  mastery — heresy crushed, Netherlands subjugated, France and England as client
  states; only Scandinavia, Poland, Muscovy, and Ottoman lands would have escaped

### Chronology of the Three Great Struggles

**Phase 1 — Italian Wars (to ~1559)**
- French invasions of Italy since 1494 → coalitions forced them out repeatedly
- **Francis I** (1515–1547) vs. **Charles V**: defeated and captured at **Battle of
  Pavia (1525)**; back at war in the 1530s–1540s
- Unholy alliance: **Ottoman sultan** + Francis I; French-Ottoman fleets attacked
  Nice in 1542
- Charles V defeated Protestant princes at **Battle of Mühlberg (1547)**, but
  success merely rallied more foes; French armies moved into Germany 1552
- **Peace of Augsburg (1555)**: temporary end to German religious wars
- **Treaty of Cateau-Cambresis (1559)**: ended Franco-Spanish conflict

**Phase 2 — Netherlands Revolt and the Armada Period (~1560s–1609)**
- **Philip II**'s religious intolerance + heavy taxation → revolt in the Netherlands
- **Duke of Alba** dispatched; military despotism provoked full Dutch resistance in
  Holland and Zeeland; alarmed England, France, northern Germany
- Philip annexed **Portugal** (1580), adding its colonies and fleet — intensifying
  fears of Spanish dominance
- **Spanish Armada (1588)**: failed; two later invasion attempts also failed
- **Elizabeth I** of England lent support to Dutch rebels; **Henry of Navarre**
  converted from Protestantism to Catholicism to unite France against Spain
- **Peace of Vervins (1598)**: Spain abandoned French interference
- England-Spain peace (1604); Dutch truce **(1609)**
- Verdict: Spain could not crush the Netherlands by sea or through Maurice of
  Nassau's efficient land/water defenses; European plurality survived

**Phase 3 — Thirty Years War (1618–1648)**
- Bohemian Protestant revolt against **Ferdinand II** (emperor 1619–1637) lit the
  fuse; Habsburg forces initially fared well with Spanish general **Spinola**
- **Cardinal Richelieu** of France stirred up trouble behind the scenes; **Christian
  IV** of Denmark invaded from the north (1626) — both failed
- **Wallenstein**, Ferdinand's general, was imposing centralized authority across
  Germany into the Baltic by the late 1620s
- **Gustavus Adolphus II** of Sweden (1611–1632): moved into Germany 1630, burst
  into Rhineland/Bavaria in 1631; killed at **Battle of Lützen (1632)**, but Swedish
  role continued
- **Philip IV** + first minister **Count-Duke of Olivares** sent a major Spanish army
  into the Rhineland (1634) → forced Richelieu into open French intervention (1635)

> "Either all is lost, or else Castile will be head of the world."
> — Olivares, 1635, planning triple invasion of France

- Habsburg forces briefly approached Paris but were overstretched; Portuguese
  revolt (1640) and Catalan revolt (aided by France) drained Spanish resources;
  Dutch struck at Brazil, Angola, Ceylon — arguably the **first global war**
- Armies of the 1640s smaller than those of the 1630s; financial exhaustion widespread;
  no single party could withdraw without risk of betrayal by allies

### Peace Settlements

- **Peace of Westphalia (1648)**: Spain made separate peace with Dutch (recognizing
  independence) to deprive France of an ally; confirmed religious and political *balance*
  within the Holy Roman Empire; limited imperial authority
- Franco-Spanish war continued as pure national rivalry; **Mazarin** allied with
  **Cromwell**'s Protestant England in 1655 to deliver final blows to Spain
- **Treaty of the Pyrenees (1659)**: terms not particularly harsh, but revealed that
  the age of Habsburg predominance was over; European plurality confirmed

### The Military Revolution

- Wars of the 1630s were vastly larger in men and money than those of the 1520s
- A "military revolution" transformed fighting in this period, making it far more
  expensive — financial capacity to sustain war became the decisive variable
  (examined in detail in next section)

<!-- pp. 81-100 -->

## Chapter 2 (cont.): The Habsburg Bid for Mastery — Strengths and Weaknesses

### End of Habsburg Predominance

- By 1668 Spain formally recognized Portuguese independence — the
  last remnant of **Philip IV**'s ambitions reduced to preserving
  Iberian unity, which it could not even manage
- Europe's political fragmentation remained essentially as it had
  been at **Charles V**'s accession in 1519 — Spain paid the price
  of its original strategical overextension

---

### Why Did the Habsburgs Fail?

- Kennedy explicitly rejects personal explanations: the madness of
  **Emperor Rudolf II** or incompetence of **Philip III** don't
  account for a 140-year failure pattern
- The puzzle is greater given the *scale* of Habsburg material
  resources — no other European power came close

### Habsburg Strengths: Finance

- ~1/4 of early modern Europe's population lived in Habsburg territory
- **Five chief revenue sources:**
  1. **Castile** — directly ruled; sales tax (*alcabala*), "crusade"
     tax on church property, Cortes grants; the most reliable base
  2. **Italian states** (richest trading regions in Europe) —
     mercantile wealth and mobile capital
  3. **Low Countries** — second great trading nexus
  4. **American empire** — the "royal fifth" of silver/gold, plus
     sales taxes, customs, church levies in the New World; American
     treasure also helped private hands pay rising state taxes, and
     the crown could borrow against expected silver fleet arrivals
  5. **Banking/mercantile houses** — southern German, Italian
     (Antwerp) financiers within Habsburg territory; more reliable
     than the Reichstag, which voted money only when Turks were at
     the door

- In the postfeudal age, cash and credit were *absolutely essential*
  — ships, provisions, mercenary wages all required direct payment
  or promise of payment in a market economy

### Habsburg Strengths: Military

- **Army of Flanders** — composed of six nationalities; loyal to the
  Catholic cause but still required regular pay
- Naval strength: Mediterranean galleys + Genoese/Neapolitan carracks
  + Portuguese fleet reinforcing Castilian and Aragonese armadas
- Greatest military asset: the **Spanish tercio** — integrated
  regiments of up to 3,000 pikemen, swordsmen, and arquebusiers;
  introduced by **Gonzalo de Córdoba** ("the Great Captain")
  - Most effective infantry in Europe from early 16th century through
    mid-Thirty Years War
  - At **Nördlingen (1634)**: resisted 15 charges by Swedish army,
    then advanced to crush the enemy
  - At **Rocroi (1643)**: still fighting grimly when surrounded;
    Spanish power cracked *visibly* only when the army consisted
    mainly of German, Italian, and Irish mercenaries — fewer Castilians

> "Soldiering had become a fashionable and profitable occupation not
> only for the gentry but for the whole population." — Lynch, on
> Castile as a recruiting ground

---

### The "Military Revolution" — Factor One in Habsburg Failure

- **Military revolution** (c. 1520s onward): massive increase in the
  scale, costs, and organization of war over ~150 years
- Infantry supplanted cavalry as the decisive arm — cheaper to
  equip and feed, infantry could be recruited in larger numbers
- **Tracé italien** (sophisticated bastion fortifications) required
  enormous numbers of troops to man or besiege
- Army sizes exploded:
  - Pre-1529: no state fielded more than 30,000 effectives
  - 1536–37: Charles V mobilized 60,000 in Lombardy alone
  - 1552: Charles commanded ~150,000 total across all fronts
  - 1574: Army of Flanders alone = 86,000
  - 1625: Philip IV commanded 300,000 men
- Naval costs paralleled land costs: by 1574 Philip II supporting
  146 galleys — nearly triple the number a dozen years before

### Spiraling Costs and Chronic Insolvency

- General inflation (food prices ×5, industrial prices ×3,
  1500–1630) compounded by doubling and redoubling of army/navy size
- **Charles V's fiscal crises:**
  - 1540s campaigns vs. Algiers, France, and German Protestants
    exhausted both ordinary *and* extraordinary income; revenues
    pledged to bankers years in advance
  - 1552 Metz campaign cost 2.5 million ducats — ~10× his normal
    annual American income
  - Driven to raise fresh loans on progressively worse terms; interest
    payments consumed most of ordinary revenue
  - Abdicated leaving Philip II a Spanish debt of ~20 million ducats

- **Philip II's fiscal crises:**
  - 1557: Spanish crown declared bankruptcy; the **Fuggers** and
    other great banking houses brought to their knees simultaneously
  - France also went bankrupt in 1557 — the mutual exhaustion that
    drove **Cateau-Cambresis (1559)**
  - Philip's revenues doubled 1556–73 alone, more than redoubled by
    end of reign — but outgoings were far larger
  - **Lepanto (1571)** campaign: 4 million ducats annually (shared
    with Venice and the papacy)
  - 1575: suspended interest payments to Genoese bankers → troops in
    Flanders mutinied
  - American silver (c. 2 million ducats/year by 1580s, vs. 200,000
    earlier) temporarily rescued credit
  - **Armada (1588)**: cost 10 million ducats; its failure was a
    financial as well as naval disaster
  - 1596: defaulted again; at death (1598) debts totaled 100 million
    ducats; interest payments = ~2/3 of all revenues
  - 1607: further bankruptcy; truce with Dutch (1609) forced by army
    mutinies

- Pattern for next 30 years: scrape fresh loans, new taxes, windfall
  from Americas → fund a major campaign → grinding costs erode the
  gains → worse position than before
- By 1640s (after Catalan and Portuguese revolts + reduced American
  treasure), long slow decline was inevitable

> "What other fate was due to a nation which, although providing
> formidable fighters, was directed by governments which consistently
> spent two or three times more than the ordinary revenues provided?"

---

### Strategical Overextension — Factor Two

- Habsburgs had **too much to do, too many enemies, too many fronts**
  — forces dispersed across Sicily, Italy, North Africa, Netherlands,
  New World, Germany
- Kennedy's analogy: "Spain resembled a large bear in the pit: more
  powerful than any of the dogs attacking it, but never able to deal
  with all of its opponents"
- Unlike France, England, Sweden, or even the Ottomans, Spain *never*
  enjoyed sustained periods of peace and recovery — it lurched from
  one enemy directly to the next
  - Peace with France → war with Turks; truce in Mediterranean →
    extended Atlantic conflict → struggle for NW Europe
  - During worst periods, fighting on three fronts simultaneously,
    with enemies consciously aiding each other diplomatically and
    commercially

- Historians argued Charles V and successors should have set defense
  priorities — but which commitments were expendable?
  - **New World**: unthinkable to abandon; provided the revenue
    without which the entire war effort collapsed
  - **Italy**: abandoning it would give France a power vacuum and
    leave the Mediterranean flank open to the Ottomans; Italy was
    Spain's outer bulwark against Turkish westward expansion
  - **Netherlands**: by elimination, the one area where losses
    *might* have been cut — and indeed the costliest front of all

### The Netherlands Trap

- Between 1566–1654 Spain sent at least **218 million ducats** to
  the Military Treasury in the Netherlands — considerably more than
  the total crown receipts from the Indies (121 million ducats)
- The Army of Flanders consumed ~1/4 of total Spanish government
  outgoings decade after decade
- Yet abandoning Flanders was politically impossible to Madrid:
  1. **Reputation**: loss to France or United Provinces would enhance
     Spain's most dangerous enemies
  2. **Buffer argument** (Philip IV's advisers): fighting there
     diverted enemies from Spain itself

> "Although the war which we have fought in the Netherlands has
> exhausted our treasury and forced us into the debts that we have
> incurred, it has also diverted our enemies in those parts so that,
> had we not done so, it is certain that we would have had war in
> Spain or somewhere nearer." — Philip IV's council

  3. **Domino theory**: if Netherlands fell, so would Germany, then
     Italy, then America — Spanish statesmen perceived an
     interconnected strategic whole

> "The first and greatest dangers [1635] are those that threaten
> Lombardy, the Netherlands and Germany. A defeat in any of these
> three is fatal for this Monarchy... Germany will be followed by
> Italy and the Netherlands, and the Netherlands will be followed
> by America; and Lombardy will be followed by Naples and Sicily."

---

### Failure to Mobilize Resources Efficiently — Factor Three

- Habsburg empire was a **congeries of territories**, each with its
  own privileges — no central administration, legislature, or
  judiciary; only the monarch himself was the connecting link
- **Intense localism** meant taxpayers of Sicily/Naples paid for
  Mediterranean fleets but bitterly refused to fund Netherlands wars;
  Portuguese supported New World defense but not German campaigns

- **Italy's net contribution**: despite theoretical capacity, Spain
  had to send millions *to* Italy during Mediterranean wars; over
  1519–1659 as a whole, Italian possessions may not have contributed
  more to the common fund than they received for their own defense

- **Netherlands**: began as a growing tax contributor under Charles V;
  by 1565 state debt of Low Countries reached 10 million florins;
  after revolt broke out, the region became a colossal drain rather
  than a source

- **Castile as "milch cow"**: the entire Spanish fiscal system rested
  on Castile (Aragon, Catalonia, Valencia had their own autonomous
  tax systems; Portugal completely autonomous fiscally after 1580)
  - Even within Castile, Basque provinces were immune
  - Key taxes: *alcabala* (10% sales tax), *servicios* (Cortes
    grants), *millones* (foodstuffs tax) — all fell on trade and the
    poor, spreading impoverishment and depopulation by emigration

- American silver provided only ~1/4 to 1/3 of what Castile itself
  generated even at peak — the whole war effort rested on ~6 million
  Castilian peasants and merchants

### Spain's Self-Defeating Economic Policies

- Early 16th century Castile was relatively prosperous — growing
  population, significant industries
- Counter-Reformation and continuous warfare strengthened religious
  and military elements while weakening commercial ones
- Economic incentives pointed toward acquiring a church benefice or
  purchasing a patent of minor nobility — not productive enterprise
- Chronic lack of skilled craftsmen (armaments); guilds obstructed
  labor mobility and innovation
- **The Mesta** (guild of sheep owners): granted wide grazing rights
  that retarded agricultural development; Mesta's payments went to
  royal treasury so the crown wouldn't reform it
- By 1640: three-quarters of goods in Spanish ports delivered in
  *Dutch* ships — enriching their greatest enemies
- Constant trade imbalance bridged only by re-export of American
  silver

- **Debt spiral mechanics:**
  - Interest-bearing government bonds (*juros*) diverted investment
    from trade and industry
  - By 1543: 65% of ordinary revenue spent on *juro* interest alone
  - Crown repeatedly debased silver coinage with copper (*vellon*)
  - Crown seized incoming American silver destined for private
    individuals, forced them to accept *juros* in compensation
  - Declaring temporary bankruptcy reduced Madrid's future credit rating

- **Policy failures compounding decline** (Kennedy's list):
  - Expulsion of the Jews, then the Moriscos (lost skilled commercial
    communities)
  - Closing contacts with foreign universities
  - Biscayan shipyards ordered to build large warships only —
    excluding smaller, more useful trading vessels
  - Sale of monopolies restricting trade
  - Heavy taxes on wool exports → uncompetitive in foreign markets
  - Internal customs barriers between Spanish kingdoms → drove up
    prices and hurt commerce

> "The flood of precious metals from the Indies was to Spain as
> water on a roof — it poured on and then was drained away."

- Core failure: Spain never recognized the importance of preserving
  the economic underpinnings of military power; causes of decline
  existed for decades before they became visible in the 1640s

---

### Austria vs. Spain: Divergent Fates

- Habsburg Austria failed to defeat Protestantism in Germany but
  achieved a **consolidation** of its dynastic lands (Austria,
  Bohemia, etc.)
- With that territorial base + later creation of a professional
  standing army, Austria reemerged as a European great power in the
  later 17th century — just as Spain entered its steepest decline
- Spain, overextended in all directions, was weak at heart by
  mid-17th century; Austria's recovery was no consolation to Madrid

---

## International Comparisons (Section Begins)

- Habsburg failure was *relative* — all European states faced the
  "military revolution" challenge of supervising and financing
  ever-larger forces

**Table 1: Military Manpower, 1470–1660**

| Date  | Spain   | United Provinces | France  | England | Sweden |
|-------|---------|-----------------|---------|---------|--------|
| 1470s | 20,000  | —               | 40,000  | 25,000  | —      |
| 1550s | 150,000 | —               | 50,000  | 20,000  | —      |
| 1590s | 200,000 | 20,000          | 80,000  | 30,000  | 15,000 |
| 1630s | 300,000 | 50,000          | 150,000 | —       | 45,000 |
| 1650s | 100,000 | —               | 100,000 | 70,000  | 70,000 |

- Omitted from survey: the **Ottoman Empire** (discussed prior
  chapter; its problems — strategical overextension, inefficient
  resource mobilization, suppression of commercial enterprise —
  mirror the Habsburg failures)
- Also omitted: Russia, Prussia (not yet great powers); Poland-
  Lithuania (hampered by ethnic diversity, serfdom, elective monarchy
  — "an aristocratic anarchy which was to make it a byword for
  political ineptitude")

### France: Comparison Begins

- **France** ultimately replaced Spain as the greatest military power
  — but for most of this chapter's period, France was *decidedly
  weaker* than Spain
- Post-Hundred Years War strengths: consolidated territory vs.
  England/Burgundy/Brittany; *taille* (poll tax levied without
  States General consent); professional secretaries of state; royal
  army with powerful artillery
- But fragility soon exposed: Italian wars were expensive disasters;
  French crown also declared bankruptcy in **1557**
- Before that crash: borrowing at 10–16% from financiers; selling
  offices
- After 1560: religious rivalries + great noble houses produced a
  bloody civil war — France threatened to become the new cockpit of
  Europe rather than a great power

<!-- pp. 101-120 -->

## Chapter 2 (continued): The Habsburg Bid for Mastery, and Its Failure

### France: Recovery Under Henry IV and Fiscal Collapse Under Richelieu

- **Henry IV** (1589–1610) secured peace with Spain (1598) and stabilized France
  after decades of civil war, religious conflict, and near-fiscal ruin
- By 1596 France's national debt was ~300 million livres; four-fifths
  of annual revenue had already been alienated
- **Sully**, Henry IV's finance minister, restored solvency without new taxes:
  overhauled tax collection, flushed out fraudulent exemptions, recovered
  crown lands, renegotiated national debt interest — budget balanced within
  a few years of 1600
- France's latent advantage: population of ~16 million (2x Spain, 4x England),
  diversified agriculture, food surplus — but required competent leadership
  to realize these assets
- Henry IV's assassination (1610) broke the recovery; between 1610 and
  **Richelieu**'s consolidation in the 1630s, internal factions and Huguenot
  dissent paralyzed France's capacity to act as a Great Power
- From 1635 onward, war against the Habsburgs forced desperate fiscal measures:
  taille doubled by 1643, sale of offices accelerated; yet government
  expenditure was nearly double income in 1643 (the year of Rocroi)
- **Mazarin**, Richelieu's successor, pushed even more extreme fiscal extraction;
  the 1648 revolt began as a tax strike against Mazarin and swiftly produced
  a government bankruptcy declaration
- After the Peace of Westphalia (1648), eleven more years of Franco-Spanish
  war continued — both powers were "punch-drunk boxers," near financial
  collapse, unable to finish each other off
- France's army (under **d'Enghien** and **Turenne**) was becoming the finest
  in Europe, but **Richelieu**'s navy had disintegrated under land-war pressures
- England under **Cromwell** tipped the balance by joining the conflict against
  Spain; the **Treaty of the Pyrenees** (1659) reflected Spain's exhaustion
  more than French greatness

### The "Flank" Powers: England

- Kennedy's broader argument: each power had strengths and weaknesses; the
  real question was whether weaknesses could be kept from outweighing strengths
- **Henry VII** (post-Wars of the Roses) restored English solvency through
  domestic fiscal prudence — paid debts, cut expenses, encouraged wool trade
  and commerce; customs revenues, recovered crown lands, and Star Chamber
  profits produced a healthy surplus
- Critical caveat: fiscal stability ≠ military power; England's 3–4 million
  population was dwarfed by France and Spain; financial infrastructure
  was primitive compared to Italy, Germany, and the Low Countries
- **Henry VIII** dissolved his father's army, forbade private magnate armies;
  no regular standing force existed during Franco-Habsburg wars; had to hire
  German pikemen and arquebusiers for continental campaigns
- Henry VIII's French campaigns of 1513 and 1520s/1540s were not military
  disasters, but financially catastrophic: in 1513 alone, £632,000 of a
  £700,000 treasury outlay went to military purposes; wars of the 1540s
  cost £2,135,000 — roughly 10x normal crown income
- Thomas Cromwell's seizure of church lands (1530s) temporarily doubled royal
  revenues; permitted fortress-building and naval expansion; but Henry VIII
  squandered the windfall on disastrous French wars
- Final resort: coin debasement, forced loans, sale of monastic properties
  at discounts, borrowing from the **Fuggers** — settlement with France in
  1550 was relief for a near-bankrupt government
- **Elizabeth I** recognized England's limits clearly: could not match Spain or
  France directly, so maintained independence by diplomacy and "cold war"
  at sea — economical and occasionally profitable
- Elizabeth built a healthy surplus in her first 25 years, which she needed
  when war with Spain finally came (expedition to Netherlands, 1585)
- Naval commanders **Hawkins**, **Raleigh**, **Drake** urged intercepting Spanish
  silver and raiding colonies; Elizabeth also had to commit troops to the
  Netherlands and northern France — not from love of Dutch rebels but because,
  as she argued: *"whenever the last day of France came it would also be
  the eve of the destruction of England"*
- War costs soared: Netherlands subsidies alone were £100,000–£175,000/year
  in 1586–87; by her final four years annual outgoings exceeded £500,000
  (vs. ~£200,000 in the early 1580s)
- Elizabeth never declared bankruptcy or failed to pay troops — a genuine
  achievement — but she left **James I** in debt and dependent on a
  mistrustful Parliament and cautious London money market
- England's Crown-Parliament conflict (1603–1640s) over finance paralyzed
  the country during the **Thirty Years War**; the Ship Money controversy
  that might have funded military power instead triggered civil war
- **Cromwell**'s **New Model Army** finally closed the quality gap with continental
  forces; trained on **Maurice of Nassau** and **Gustavus Adolphus** lines,
  it defeated Spain at the Battle of the Dunes (1658)
- The Commonwealth navy underwent a renaissance: fleet doubled from 39 ships
  (1649) to 80 (1651), conditions improved, Commons funded it enthusiastically
  — used against the Dutch (1652–54) and then the Spanish Empire
- Cromwell's war against Spain cost £2,878,000 in 1657 alone (£1.9M army,
  £742K navy); spending was "four times as much as had been thought
  intolerable under Charles I" — debts mounted, merchant classes pleaded
  for peace
- Key Kennedy point: England and the United Provinces, unlike other powers,
  had developed **efficient market economies** that combined rising living
  standards with growing populations — providing a more durable fiscal base

### The "Flank" Powers: Sweden

- Sweden in 1611 was a pigmy: 900,000–1.25 million people (including Finland),
  mostly Arctic waste and forest, 95% peasantry, barter economy, no middle
  class, almost no industry — defeated badly by Denmark in 1611–13
- **Two factors** transformed Sweden rapidly:
  1. **Foreign entrepreneurs** (especially Dutch, also Germans and Walloons)
     — **Louis de Geer** most famous: built timber mills, foundries, factories,
     made loans to the king, drew Sweden into the Amsterdam mercantile system.
     Sweden became Europe's largest iron and copper producer; export revenues
     funded the military; Sweden achieved self-sufficiency in armaments
  2. **Internal reforms** by **Gustavus Adolphus**: overhauled courts, treasury,
     tax system, chancery, education; channeled nobility into state service;
     built a navy to control the Baltic; and above all, created a national
     standing army based on conscription, new battlefield tactics, mobile
     light artillery, disciplined cavalry
- By summer of 1630 when Gustavus entered Germany, he had perhaps the best
  army in the world; within 18 months it had grown to ~150,000 — but
  four-fifths were foreign mercenaries (Scots, English, Germans), fearfully expensive
- Key insight: **the Swedes did not pay for their German army** — it was
  largely self-financing through "contributions" exacted from friendly German
  states and ransoms from hostile ones (**Wallenstein** had pioneered the same
  method for the Habsburgs). At the Peace of Westphalia, the Swedish army
  was still looting Bohemia and withdrew only on payment of "compensation"
- Sweden's war machine was thus **parasitic**: formidable on the march through
  Germany, but unsustainable from Sweden's own economic base, which had
  been strained by crown-land sales and heavy peasant taxation
- Post-1648 Sweden's trans-Baltic possessions (Estonia, Livonia, Bremen,
  Pomerania) cost more to defend in peacetime than the German campaigns had
- Under **Charles X** and **Charles XI**, Sweden remained a regional Baltic
  power but was economically too small to compete with France, England, or
  the United Provinces — its foreign trade c. 1700 was a tiny fraction of
  the Dutch or English, its state expenditure perhaps one-fiftieth of France's
- The Baltic balance of power was itself being manipulated by France, England,
  and the Dutch through subsidies and diplomatic intervention

> "For a generation Sweden had been drunk with victory and bloated with booty:
> Charles XI led her back into the grey light of everyday existence, gave her
> policies appropriate to her resources and her real interests, equipped her
> to carry them out, and prepared for her a future of weight and dignity as
> a second-class power."
> — Professor Roberts

### The Dutch Republic: Finance as the Foundation of Power

- The **United Provinces** offers the starkest contrast: a tiny cluster of
  seven heterogeneous provinces, no natural-resource advantages, restricted
  territory and population — yet became a Great Power inside and outside
  Europe for nearly a century
- Dutch military power and naval dominance were **consequences** of its
  commercial-financial strength, not the essence of it
- The revolt against Habsburg rule was initially chaotic and nearly suppressed:
  by the 1580s the **Duke of Parma**'s reconquest campaign nearly succeeded,
  halted only by English subsidies, English guns, and Spain's diversion
  into France
- Since Dutch ports and shipyards remained in rebel hands, Spain could never
  control the sea — Parma could only advance by slow, landward sieges which
  lost momentum whenever he had to march into France
- By the 1590s **Maurice of Nassau** had built a disciplined force: in 1600,
  only 17 Dutch companies out of 113 total (rest: English, French, Scots,
  Walloon, German) — yet regularly paid, unlike most European armies
- Holland's war costs: 960,000 florins in 1579 → 5.5 million by 1599 →
  10 million florins annually by the early seventeenth century
- Spain's greater financial exhaustion caused the **Truce of 1609**; Dutch
  economy was growing fast enough to make the burden bearable, then serviceable

### Dutch Economic Foundations

- Growth driven by: refugee influx from the south (Antwerp's sack by Spain
  in 1576 boosted Amsterdam); herring trade dominance; land reclamation;
  the **fluyt** (simple, cheap bulk freighter) — Dutch vessels carried
  timber, grain, cloth, salt, herrings across all of Europe's waterways
- Raw materials imported and "finished" in Amsterdam, Delft, Leyden — sugar
  refining, distilling, silk, glass, armaments, printing among chief industries;
  by 1622, 56% of Holland's 670,000 people lived in medium-sized towns
- Overseas: 25 ships/year to West Africa, 20 to Brazil, 10 to East Indies,
  150 to Caribbean (1598–1605); colonies at Amboina and Ternate; trading
  posts around the Indian Ocean, Amazon mouth, and Japan
- **Amsterdam** as financial center: deposits at interest, bills of exchange,
  clearing, public loans — similar to Venice and Genoa in type, but larger,
  more certain, and with government investors who had every incentive to
  maintain sound credit
- Dutch government could borrow more cheaply than any rival because it
  **reliably repaid debts** — a compounding advantage in every war

### Dutch War Finance

- After war resumed with Spain (1621), armed forces costs rose from 13.4M
  florins (1622) to 18.8M florins (1640)
- Province of Holland's debt reached 153 million florins by 1651 — but
  interest was consistently repaid, so the credit system never collapsed
- Kennedy's conclusion: "as long as success in war depended upon the length
  of one's purse, the Dutch were always likely to outstay the others"

---

### War, Money, and the Nation-State (Chapter Synthesis)

- The post-1450 **"birth of the nation-state"** was inseparable from the
  demands of modern warfare — centralization of authority, expanded taxation,
  and elaborate bureaucratic machinery all arose primarily to fund armies
- Causes of nation-state formation: economic change undermining feudalism;
  the Reformation merging civil and religious authority (*cuius regio, eius
  religio*); decline of Latin in favor of vernacular language; printing;
  oceanic discovery heightening awareness of national difference
- But **war was the most urgent driver**: military technology (infantry, artillery,
  expensive fortifications, fleets) forced states to spend more than ever
  before and to develop correspondingly larger revenue systems
- In Elizabeth I's last years and Philip II's Spain: up to **three-quarters
  of all government expenditure** went to war or debt repayment for past wars
- Military machines of the era were deeply inefficient: ragtag troops, disloyal
  mercenaries, inadequate supply, unstandardized weapons, rampant corruption
- **The Army of Flanders mutinied 46 times between 1572 and 1607** — lack of
  pay was as dangerous as enemy action

> "History knows many more armies ruined by want and disorder than by the
> efforts of their enemies; and I have witnessed how all the enterprises
> which were embarked on in my day were lacking for that reason alone."
> — **Richelieu**, *Testament Politique*

- Gustavus Adolphus's celebrated mobile campaigns in Germany were driven not
  by Clausewitzian strategy but by the need to find food and fodder for
  150,000 men
- No state, however prosperous, could pay immediately for a prolonged war;
  the gap between income and expenditure was always closed by loans — from
  private bankers like the **Fuggers** or later from organized government
  bond markets — but spiraling costs repeatedly forced defaults and debasements
- Kennedy's key argument: the Habsburg failure was not absolute — **all**
  states were under severe strain. Victory was a marginal, relative achievement.
  The anti-Habsburg coalition succeeded by slightly better balancing their
  material base against military power, recognizing that "the trader and the
  manufacturer and the farmer were as important as the cavalry officer and
  the pikeman"

> "It had been, to borrow the later words of the Duke of Wellington, a
> 'damned close-run thing.' Most great contests are."

---

## Chapter 3 (cont.): The Financial Revolution and Geopolitics, 1660–1815

### The Five-Power System Takes Shape

- Between **Louis XIV**'s assumption of power (1660–1661) and Waterloo (1815),
  older powers (Ottoman Empire, Spain, Netherlands, Sweden) fell to second rank
- A crude **trilateral equilibrium** formed: France in the west vs.
  **Prussia** and **Habsburg Empire** in the east
- The most significant changes occurred on the *flanks* of Europe:
  - Britain expanded its maritime empire globally
  - Russia expanded eastward and southward across Asia
- Both flank powers stayed deeply involved in European center affairs
  (Britain via Hanover dynastic link from 1714; Russia over Poland)
- By mid-18th century, the system was one of **five Great Powers**:
  France, Habsburg Empire, Prussia, Britain, Russia

### Why Military Technology Didn't Explain the Rankings

- Purely military/technological explanations fail — Wellington's army
  in 1815 was not significantly more advanced than Marlborough's in 1710
- Small-scale improvements existed (flintlock rifle, **Gribeauval** mobile
  artillery, the **carronade** naval gun from Carrón Company, Scotland, 1770s)
- Most important military change was in **organization**, not hardware:
  - France under Louis XIV (1661–1715) pioneered bureaucratic war ministry
  - **Colbert** and **Le Tellier** created the French war ministry model
  - **Martinet** as inspector general imposed new training/discipline standards
  - Creation of barracks, hospitals, depots, standing armies, royal navies
- State monopolization of military power = central to nation-building;
  it gave armed forces a degree of *permanence* previously absent
- Such organizational gains were quickly copied (e.g., **Peter the Great**
  transformed Russia's army in a few decades after 1698)
- Two factors mattered far more than military: **finance** and **geography**

---

## The "Financial Revolution"

### Why Finance Became Decisive

- The seven major Anglo-French wars (1689–1815) were wars of *endurance*
  — victory went to the coalition with the greatest capacity to sustain credit
- These were coalition wars: a fading belligerent would look to a richer
  ally for loans and reinforcements rather than accept defeat
- Cost of war escalated dramatically:
  - Sixteenth century: millions of pounds
  - Late seventeenth century: *tens* of millions
  - Close of Napoleonic Wars: occasionally £100 million *a year*
- No state could pay for wars out of ordinary revenue; massive tax
  increases risked domestic unrest while fighting foreign enemies
- Solution: **borrowing** — selling long-term negotiable bonds paying
  interest to all who advanced money to the state
- This two-way system of raising and simultaneously spending vast sums
  acted like a bellows, fanning western capitalism and the nation-state

### The Dutch Model

- **United Provinces** led the way in public credit:
  - Merchants were part of the government; they demanded the same
    financial rectitude as in a joint-stock company
  - **States General** raised taxes efficiently and kept interest rates low,
    making long-term funded state debt seem perfectly normal
  - **Amsterdam** became the world's financial capital: clearing bills,
    exchanging currency, providing credit to foreign governments
- Amsterdam's surplus capital invested in foreign government bonds —
  Dutch loan terms to Russia, Spain, Austria, Poland, Sweden served as
  a market rating of each country's **economic potential and creditworthiness**
  - Polish government stock plummeted late 18th century
  - Austria's credit proved remarkably durable across decades
- Long-term consequence for the Dutch: steady returns from government
  loans shifted the economy toward *rentier* status, disinclining bankers
  from industrial risk capital; excise duties to service debt made wages
  uncompetitive — a structural trap

### Britain vs. France: The Critical Comparison

- Older view (Britain = industrial strength, France = backward ancien régime)
  is an oversimplification:
  - France had a less regressive tax system in some respects
  - France was moving toward industrial "takeoff," had considerable
    armaments production and skilled artisans
  - France's population and agricultural revenues *dwarfed* Britain's
  - Its *dirigiste* regime seemed more coherent than Westminster party politics
- Despite this, **Britain held decisive financial advantages**:

**British advantages:**
- Taxes were mostly "invisible" (excise on basic goods, customs)
  — less resented than France's vast army of tax farmers and collectors
- No *internal* tolls (which stifled French domestic commerce)
- British land tax had no privileged exemptions
- Taxes authorized by elected Parliament — more legitimate than
  the *ancien régime*
- Light peacetime taxation preserved private savings for investment capital,
  *and* created a vast reserve of taxable wealth for wartime
- By the Napoleonic Wars, Britain (half France's population) raised
  *more* absolute tax revenue than France each year

**The Bank of England and public credit:**
- Creation of **Bank of England** in 1694 (initially a wartime expedient)
  enabled long-term loans raised efficiently with guaranteed interest repayment
- Growth of national debt, stock exchange, and "country banks"
  expanded money supply without severe inflation
- Parliamentary guarantee of state obligations gave investors confidence
- Ministries from **Walpole** to the younger **Pitt** cultivated reputation
  for financial rectitude
- After the **South Sea Bubble** of 1720: "for the rest of the century
  it remained more honest, as well as more efficient, than that of
  any other in Europe"
- Result: British government bonds increasingly attractive to Dutch
  investors; even when Dutch alliance lapsed, Dutch capital kept flowing
  to London (except during the American Revolutionary War, when
  British creditworthiness was lowest)

> "Credit was the principal advantage that England hath over France."
> — *Bishop Berkeley*

**British Wartime Expenditure and Revenue, 1688–1815 (Table 2):**
| Period | Total Expenditure | Total Income | Loans | Loans as % |
|--------|-----------------|--------------|-------|------------|
| 1688–97 | £49.3M | £32.8M | £16.6M | 33.6% |
| 1702–13 | £93.6M | £64.2M | £29.4M | 31.4% |
| 1739–48 | £95.6M | £65.9M | £29.7M | 31.1% |
| 1756–63 | £160.6M | £100.6M | £60.0M | 37.4% |
| 1776–83 | £236.5M | £141.9M | £94.6M | 39.9% |
| 1793–1815 | £1,657.9M | £1,217.6M | £440.3M | 26.6% |

- Britain "spend on war out of all proportion to its tax revenue,
  and thus throw into the struggle the decisive margin of ships and
  men without which the resources previously committed might have
  been committed in vain"
- Admiralty contracts for iron, wood, cloth created a **feedback loop**
  stimulating British industrial production and technological breakthroughs

### France's Structural Financial Failures

- France had **no proper system of public finance** — from the Middle Ages,
  financial operations "managed" by a cluster of middlemen:
  municipal governments, clergy, provincial estates, **tax farmers**
- Each collector took a cut before passing money up; each also received
  5% interest on the price paid for office; senior officials paid
  contractors directly without handing funds to the royal treasury
- "The real culprit was the system itself" — systemic corruption,
  not just individual venality
- No national accounting until **Necker**'s reforms in the 1770s;
  escalating national debt was of little concern to the monarchy
- French surplus capital tended toward purchasing offices or annuities
  rather than investing in business — contrast with Britain where
  rising debt *boosted* commercial investment
- Every attempt to create a French national bank was resisted by
  those with interests in the existing system

**La Rochelle vs. Liverpool/Glasgow — case study in commercial disadvantage:**
- La Rochelle well-positioned for triangular Atlantic trade (West Africa,
  West Indies) but suffered from crown's "insatiable fiscal demands"
- Heavy, inequitable, arbitrarily levied taxes retarded growth;
  sale of offices diverted local capital from trade
- French government concentrated on military (land) aims, not maritime —
  so the Royal Navy repeatedly disrupted La Rochelle's trade:
  merchant ships seized, slave trade interrupted, Canadian and Louisiana
  markets eliminated
- French government allowed neutral shipping to carry colonial trade
  in wartime — making those markets harder to recover after peace
- By contrast, British Atlantic economy grew steadily throughout the
  18th century and *benefited* in wartime from Royal Navy protection
  (trade and dominion treated as inseparable)

**The post-American Revolutionary War gap:**
- Britain lost its largest colony; national debt rose to ~£220 million
- But borrowed at only 3% — annual repayment just £7.33 million
- France's American war cost at least a billion livres, virtually all
  borrowed at rates *double* Britain's
- After 1783: Britain launched Sinking Fund, consolidated revenue fund,
  improved accounts — credit strengthened (Pitt's greatest achievement)
- France: new loans each year; peacetime revenues couldn't cover
  peacetime expenditures; credit weakened further
- By late 1780s: France's national debt (~£215M) was similar to Britain's,
  but France's annual interest payments were *nearly double* — £14M vs £7M
- **Calonne**'s tax reform proposal → Assembly of Notables → calling of
  States General in 1789 → collapse of the *ancien régime*
- Link between **national bankruptcy and the French Revolution** was direct:
  government issued notes (100M livres in 1789, 200M in 1790),
  then the Constituent Assembly seized church lands and issued paper
  money — leading to inflation, exacerbated by war declared in 1792

### Finance Isn't Everything

- Amsterdam was the world's greatest financial center yet couldn't prevent
  Dutch decline as a Great Power
- Russia was economically backward and capital-starved, yet grew steadily
  in European influence
- Finance alone doesn't determine fate — geography is equally important

---

## Geopolitics

### The Geographical Factor Defined

- Kennedy's key point: geography here means not just climate, raw materials,
  or trade routes — but **strategic location**:
  - Could a power concentrate on one front or must it fight on several?
  - Did it share borders with weak or powerful states?
  - Was it a land power, sea power, or hybrid — and what did that cost?
  - Could it draw on overseas resources?

### The Dutch Geographic Trap

- United Provinces had strong early 17th century foundations:
  flourishing economy, powerful navy, well-trained army
- River network defended against Spain; North Sea position gave access
  to rich herring fisheries
- By the late 17th century, geographic vulnerabilities became decisive:
  - **Sea threat**: English mercantilist policies (Cromwell, Colbert's France)
    hurt Dutch commerce; the Channel gave English admirals weather advantage;
    shallow Dutch waters limited size of warships
  - **Land threat**: **Louis XIV**'s France from the 1660s — more dangerous
    than Spain had been a century earlier
- Dutch forced to expand army to 93,000 by 1693 and garrison southern
  border fortresses → drained resources from navy and commerce
- Dual drain: military spending spiral + severe population losses
  (static at ~2 million throughout the period)
- **William III**'s 1689 English alliance: simultaneously saved the United
  Provinces *and* contributed to its decline as an independent power —
  (Kennedy's analogy: like Lend-Lease saving Britain while undermining
  its independence, as Churchill and Roosevelt)
- Dutch forced to devote 75% of defense spending to the army (land),
  leaving maritime/colonial campaigns to Britain — which took the
  commercial benefits
- Dutch wanted to trade with France during wartime; Britain blocked it
  — reflecting Dutch dependence on *external* commerce vs. Britain's
  relative self-sufficiency
- By the Napoleonic era: Dutch ground between Britain and France,
  suffering debt repudiations, losing colonies and trade — "financial
  expertise and reliance upon 'surplus capital' was simply not enough"

### France as a Hybrid Power

- France suffered from being a **hybrid** — energies divided between
  continental aims and maritime/colonial ambitions
- Under Louis XIV, strength rested on *indigenous* resources:
  large homogeneous territory, agricultural self-sufficiency,
  population of ~20 million
  - Army grew: 30,000 (1659) → 97,000 (1666) → 350,000 (1710)
- **The strategic trap**: France was massively strong defensively but
  hemmed in by geographic barriers and rival powers in every direction:
  - South (Habsburg Netherlands): fortresses and waterways + coalition response
  - East (Germany): longer supply lines + Austro-Dutch-British coalition
  - Any alliance with Austria or Prussia drove the *other* German power
    to seek British and Russian support to neutralize France
- Every war involving maritime powers split French energies between
  Flanders/Germany/Italy on one hand and Channel/West Indies/Canada/
  Indian Ocean on the other → strategy repeatedly "fell between stools"
- France could never commit enough to challenge the Royal Navy yet kept
  funding the marine, diverting resources from the army
- **Only exception**: 1778–1783 — supporting American rebels while
  abstaining from German moves → France humiliated Britain
- In all other wars: no strategic concentration, suffered accordingly

> "In sum, the France of the *ancien régime* remained, by its size and
> population and wealth, always the greatest of the European states;
> but it was not big enough or efficiently organized enough to be a
> 'superpower,' and, restricted on land and diverted by sea, it could
> not prevail against the coalition which its ambitions inevitably
> aroused."

### The Habsburg Geographic Nightmare

- **Habsburg Empire**: awkwardly shaped conglomerate (Austria, Bohemia,
  Silesia, Moravia, Hungary, Milan, Naples, Sicily, southern Netherlands
  after 1714) — required "nightmarish diplomatic and military juggling"
  just to retain the inheritance
- Wars against Turks (1663–1664, 1683–1699, 1716–1718, 1737–1739,
  1788–1791) enhanced Balkan position but consumed most of Vienna's energy
- Classic dilemma: in 1683 with Turks at the gates, **Leopold I** had to
  stay neutral toward France despite Louis XIV's "reunions" of Alsace
  and Luxembourg that very year
- Habsburg geopolitical problem: fighting on too many fronts simultaneously,
  requiring luck and genius to manage — and often getting neither

### Key Takeaway: Finance + Geography Together

- Finance and geography frequently *interacted* — a power's geographic
  position determined how much of its finances went to unproductive
  frontier defense vs. commercial expansion
- The Dutch financial system couldn't compensate for geographic squeeze
  between Britain and France
- Russia — poor, geographically peripheral — grew in influence *because*
  its vast territory reduced vulnerability to the kinds of multi-front
  pressures that crippled France and the Netherlands
- Conclusion of section: to explain outcomes in 1660–1815 wars, neither
  finance nor geography alone suffices — both must be analyzed together

<!-- pp. 141-160 -->

## Chapter 2 (continued): The Habsburg Empire, Prussia, Russia, the United States, and Britain

### Habsburg Austria: Marginal First-Class Power

- After Prussia seized **Silesia** (1740), Vienna had to conduct every
  foreign/military decision with one eye on Berlin
- Austria needed France to check Prussia, Russia to check France, and
  Britain to check Russia — a daisy-chain of unreliable alliances
- The struggle against Prussia after 1740 was especially revealing:
  Austria could not prevail against a *smaller* German state with a
  more efficient army, revenue system, and bureaucracy
- Britain and Russia desired *neither* the elimination of Prussia nor
  Austria — balance-of-power logic froze the stalemate
- **Habsburg Empire** became a "marginal" first-class power, remaining
  so until 1918; avoided Poland's fate but defied every attempt to
  become Europe's greatest state
- Disasters were followed by *rétablissements* — reform bursts that
  revealed enormous latent resources but also how hard Vienna found it
  to mobilize them

> "The Austrian Empire's persistent, to some eyes perverse, refusal
> conveniently to disintegrate is a reminder that it possessed hidden
> strengths." — Olwen Hufton

### Prussia's Rise and Limits

- Three leaders drove Prussia's rise: **the Great Elector** (1640–1688),
  **Frederick William I** (1713–1740), **Frederick the Great** (1740–1786)
- Key enablers: Junker-officered army (up to 4/5 of taxable resources),
  fiscal stability from royal domains, foreign entrepreneurs, and the
  **General War Commissariat** bureaucracy
- Prussia also benefited from the collapse of Swedish power, Polish
  disintegration, and Habsburg distraction in the early 18th century —
  it filled a north-central European **power vacuum**
- France was far enough west to be a useful ally against Austria, not
  an existential threat; Berlin could sue Paris for peace more easily
  than Vienna or London could
- Acquisition of **Silesia** — "the industrial zone of the east" — was
  a major boost to military-economic capacity
- **Seven Years War (1756–1763)** cruelly exposed Prussia's real limits:
  only Frederick's genius and allied discoordination prevented defeat
  by encirclement; the cost in men and materiel was enormous
- By the 1770s the Prussian army was ossifying; by 1806 Napoleon
  destroyed it; even **Scharnhorst** and **Gneisenau**'s reforms could
  not conceal inadequate foundations by 1813–1815
- **Frederick William III**'s Prussia (1797–1840) was among the *least*
  of the Great Powers — it relied on British subsidies and could not
  have taken France alone

### Russia and the United States: Geographic Invulnerability

- Both future superpowers had a "crumbling frontier" (western frontier
  expansion, steppe expansion) but faced no militarily advanced
  societies threatening their home base
- Could challenge European powers while remaining insulated from the
  main European battle zones — a structural advantage the central
  powers could never enjoy

**The United States:**
- Pre-1763: American colonies were isolated coastal settlements,
  underdeveloped, mere raw-material exporters — an object fought over,
  not a power factor
- **Seven Years War** outcome (1763): France expelled from Canada/Nova
  Scotia, Spain from West Florida — freed colonists from dependence on
  British protection, enabling rebellion
- By 1776: colonial population of 2 million, doubling every 30 years,
  self-sufficient, economically prosperous — virtually unconquerable by
  naval operations alone or by a land force 3,000 miles from home
- Two major consequences of American independence:
  1. From 1783: a non-European center of production and wealth that
     would exert long-term influence on global power balance (unlike
     declining China and India)
  2. A "flank" threat to Britain — the wars of 1779–1783 and 1812–1814
     demonstrated how badly a hostile USA complicated British strategy
- US manufacturing output rose ~50x between 1776 and 1830, making it
  the 6th industrial power in the developed world by 1830
- Even in the 1790s observers predicted a great future American role

**Russia:**
- **Peter the Great** (1689–1725): created a Baltic navy, defeated
  **Sweden** at **Poltava** (1709), announced Russia as a European power
- Catherine the Great added 200,000 sq. miles by 1796; Russian forces
  temporarily occupied **Berlin** in 1760 (Seven Years War), shocking
  Frederick the Great's assumptions about his eastern neighbor
- **Suvorov**'s campaigns in Italy and the Alps (1798–1802) prefigured
  the march from Moscow to Paris (1812–1814)
- Russia's army was often larger than France's; textiles and iron
  output rising; nearly impossible to conquer from the west
- "Gunpowder empire" status let it defeat steppe horsemen and acquire
  vast new manpower, land, and raw materials
- Persistent backwardness: low per-capita income, poor communications,
  harsh climate, technological/educational retardation, incompetent
  Romanovs
- Key insight: the relative stability of 18th-century military
  technology let Russia *borrow* foreign expertise and outstrip smaller
  but more advanced states on sheer numbers — this advantage would
  erode only with the Industrial Revolution
- ~75% of state finances devoted to the military; Russian regiments
  could mount long-range operations beyond most European armies,
  though their logistical base was inadequate without allies' territory
  and British subsidies (1813–1814 march was across friendly terrain)

> De Tocqueville (early 19th century) argued Russia and the United
> States seemed "marked out by the will of Heaven to sway the
> destinies of half the globe."

### Britain: The Janus-Faced Strategy

- **Alfred Thayer Mahan**, *The Influence of Sea Power upon History*
  (1890): an island nation not forced to defend land borders can
  concentrate all effort seaward — an inherent advantage over
  continental states

> "…if a nation be so situated that it is neither forced to defend
> itself by land nor induced to seek extension of its territory by way
> of land, it has, by the very unity of its aim directed upon the sea,
> an advantage as compared with a people one of whose boundaries is
> continental." — Mahan

- Mahan's "navalist" view was *partly* correct: shift of trade routes
  from Mediterranean to Atlantic after 1500 hugely benefited an
  island on Europe's western flank; the **"virtuous triangle"** of
  trade → colonies → navy → more trade reinforced itself
- But navalism overstated: agriculture remained Britain's economic
  foundation; exports were <10% of national income until the 1780s;
  Baltic/German/Mediterranean trade mattered too
- Critical counter-point: **France dominant on land** (as in 1806–1812)
  could deliver a devastating blow to British manufacturing — European
  power politics was *not* optional for London

> "France will outdo us at sea when they have nothing to fear on land.
> I have always maintained that our marine should protect our alliances
> on the Continent, and so, by diverting the expense of France, enable
> us to maintain our superiority at sea." — Duke of Newcastle, 1742

- British **"continental" strategy** took two forms:
  1. Direct military expeditions (cheaper peripheral raids, but usually
     negligible; the substantial Marlborough/Wellington armies far
     more effective though costly)
  2. **Financial subsidies** — Frederick the Great received £675,000/yr
     from Britain 1757–1760; in the Napoleonic War, £11 million to
     allies in 1813 alone, £65 million total for the war
- British trade expansion enabled borrowing and taxation at
  unprecedented levels without national bankruptcy — funding the
  Janus-faced strategy: one face toward the Continent to balance power,
  one face toward the sea to extend maritime dominance

### Statistical Tables: Power Comparisons

**Table 3 — Populations (millions), 1700–1800:**
| State | 1700 | 1750 | 1800 |
|---|---|---|---|
| British Isles | 9.0 | 10.5 | 16.0 |
| France | 19.0 | 21.5 | 28.0 |
| Habsburg Empire | 8.0 | 18.0 | 28.0 |
| Prussia | 2.0 | 6.0 | 9.5 |
| Russia | 17.5 | 20.0 | 37.0 |
| United States | — | 2.0 | 4.0 |

**Table 4 — Army sizes (men), selected years 1690–1814:**
- Russia grows from 170,000 (1690) → 500,000 (1812/14)
- France peaks at 400,000 (1710) → 600,000 (1812/14)
- Britain: 70,000 (1690) → 250,000 (1812/14) — understates true
  contribution since it simultaneously subsidized 450,000 allied troops
  in 1813 and maintained 140,000 naval personnel

**Table 5 — Navies (ships of the line), 1689–1815:**
- Britain: 100 → 214 (virtually unchallenged throughout)
- France: 120 → 80 (peaked early, declined)
- Russia: 0 → 40 (grew steadily)

- Kennedy's warning: raw statistics mislead — France's army was
  weakened by financial/geostrategic problems; Russia's by economic
  backwardness and distance; Britain's strength was understated by
  headcount alone

---

## Chapter 3 (cont.): The Winning and Losing of Wars, 1660–1763

### Sweden's Collapse and Russia's Rise

- **Charles XII** of Sweden failed to crush the main Russian army despite
  repeated campaigns; logistics deteriorated as forces moved into Ukraine
  through the bitter winter of 1708–1709
- **Battle of Poltava (July 1709)**: Russian army vastly superior in numbers
  and position — Sweden's force wiped out; Charles fled into Turkish exile
- By the time Charles returned in December 1715, Sweden had lost its
  trans-Baltic possessions and parts of Finland to Russia
- Charles XII killed fighting the Danes in 1718; Sweden admitted loss of
  most Baltic provinces in the **1721 Peace of Nystad**
- Sweden fell to second-order power status; Peter assumed title Imperator
- Kennedy's point: Russia had proven, like France and Britain, that it
  "had the strength to act independently as a great power without
  depending on outside support"
- In **Dehio's** phrase, Russia became "a counterweight to a concentration
  at the center" — matching the balance-of-power logic operating in the west

### Anglo-French Détente and the 1730s Shift

- Post-1715 stability underwritten by an **Anglo-French détente** lasting
  nearly two decades — France needed to recuperate; war had equalized
  its interest payments with normal state revenue
- Both London and Paris monarchies feared dynastic instability and found
  cooperation mutually profitable
- By the 1730s, France under minister **Fleury** was reasserting itself:
  improved relations with Spain, diplomatic expansion in eastern Europe,
  prestige unequaled since early Louis XIV
- Britain under the isolationist **Walpole** refused to react even to
  French attacks on Austrian Lorraine and Milan (1733) and a French
  move into the Rhineland — Vienna forced into the compromise peace of 1738
- Anglo-Spanish war (1739) — reluctantly agreed to by Walpole — expanded
  when France backed Spain "beyond the line" in the Caribbean;
  **Bourbon powers** far better placed to compete overseas than in 1702–1713

### War of Austrian Succession and the Aix-la-Chapelle Settlement

- **Frederick the Great** seized Silesia in winter 1740–1741 after Emperor
  Charles VI's death and Maria Theresa's succession — transformed the situation
- Anti-Austrian France backed Prussia and Bavaria against the Habsburgs;
  Britain renewed the old Anglo-Austrian alliance and subsidized Maria Theresa
- British strategy: buy mercenaries, subsidize allies, use the Royal Navy
  to impose a tightening blockade on French commerce
- Naval war spread globally: West Indies, St. Lawrence, Madras, the Levant
- Britain ran up national debt (trebling) but overseas trade kept increasing —
  customs receipts rose even as the war ground on
- **Treaty of Aix-la-Chapelle (1748)**: geography and finance compelled
  settlement — France held the Dutch at its mercy but couldn't compensate
  for the stranglehold on its maritime commerce; Britain won colonies but
  couldn't hold the Low Countries
- Result: general return to status quo ante, *except* Frederick kept Silesia
- Aix-la-Chapelle seen by all parties as a truce, not a lasting settlement:
  Maria Theresa wanted revenge on Prussia; France wanted to win both
  land and sea; Britain wanted to crush France more decisively next time

### Road to the Seven Years War — "Diplomatic Revolution" of 1756

- Colonial clashes in North America (early 1750s) made "truce" a misnomer —
  both sides dispatched reinforcements and put navies on war footing by 1755
- Spain and United Provinces, now second-rank powers, chose neutrality;
  eastern monarchies (Austria, Prussia, Russia) could not abstain
- **France's Achilles' heel problem**: French tendency was to attack Britain
  via Hanover, which would alarm German states and compel Britain to
  subsidize continental allies — entangling east with west
- Austria determined to recover Silesia; **Czarina Elizabeth** of Russia
  wanted to punish "the disrespectful, ambitious Frederick"
  - Prussia: 150,000 men; Austria: almost 200,000; Russia: ~330,000
  - All needed western subsidies to maintain those armies
- The **"diplomatic revolution" of 1756**: France buried differences with
  the Habsburgs, joining Austria and Russia against Prussia; Berlin replaced
  Vienna as London's continental ally
- **Franco-Austro-Russian coalition** looked stronger on paper — decidedly
  bigger militarily; by 1757 Frederick had lost early gains, the Duke of
  Cumberland's army surrendered, Hanover was in doubt, Minorca fell to France

### The Seven Years War: Why the Anglo-Prussian Side Won

- **Three decisive advantages** of the Anglo-Prussian combination:
  leadership, financial staying power, and military/naval expertise

**Leadership:**
- **Frederick the Great** harnessed Prussia's full energies; brilliant
  generalship in the field (Rossbach, Leuthen — ruining French and Austrian
  armies respectively)
- **William Pitt** (the Elder) — remarkable achievement in juggling jealous
  colleagues, volatile public, a new king, while executing a coherent grand
  strategy across all theaters simultaneously
- Pitt's key insight: maritime strategy alone insufficient — must complement
  it with a "continental" one; subsidize Frederick's forces and fund an
  "Army of Observation" in Germany to protect Hanover and contain France

**Finance:**
- Britain at war's height: 120+ ships of the line, 200,000+ soldiers on
  pay lists, *plus* subsidizing Prussia
- **Seven Years War cost the Exchequer over £160 million**, of which
  £60 million (37%) raised on money markets
- Yet British overseas trade *increased every year* of the war —
  commerce funded the war machine in real time
- By contrast, all other combatants' economies suffered heavily

> "We must be merchants before we are soldiers and … the riches which
> are the true resources of this country depend upon its commerce."
> — British ambassador to Prussia (instructed by London)

- French minister **Choiseul** ruefully acknowledged the structural reality:

> "In the present state of Europe it is colonies, trade and in
> consequence sea power, which must determine the balance of power upon
> the continent. The House of Austria, Russia, the King of Prussia are
> only powers of the second rank, as are all those which cannot go to
> war unless subsidized by the trading powers."
> — Choiseul

**Naval and Military Execution:**
- **Admiral Anson** directed a Royal Navy blockade of France's Atlantic
  ports in all weathers, using a comprehensive provisioning system
- Fleet actions at Cartagena, Lagos, and **Hawke's** pursuit of Conflans's
  fleet into Quiberon Bay demonstrated British seamanship superiority
- Blockade throttled French maritime trade, protected British commerce,
  and *critically* prevented reinforcing French troops in West Indies,
  Canada, and India
- **1759 — the *annus mirabilis***: French colonies falling into British
  hands globally; Anglo-German troops routed two French armies at Minden;
  Spain entered in 1762 and suffered the same colonial fate
- Frederick: victories at Rossbach and Leuthen; later defeated Austrians
  at Liegnitz and Torgau (1760), virtually bankrupting Vienna
- Prussian costs were grinding: 60,000 soldiers lost in 1759 alone;
  Russia proved the most formidable foe due to Czarina Elizabeth's
  personal hatred of Frederick and the sheer bloodiness of each encounter
- Prussia survived until **Czarina Elizabeth's death in 1762** — new Czar
  **Peter** immediately withdrew from the war; Austria and France could
  then only settle for prewar European status quo

### Settlement of 1762–1763: Britain's Decisive Victory

- Britain the clear beneficiary: gains in West Indies, West Africa, virtual
  elimination of French influence in India, supremacy in North America
- France lost disastrously overseas *and* failed in Europe — its "lackluster
  military performance suggested the center of gravity had shifted from
  western Europe to the east"
- Evidence: France was simply disregarded during the **first partition of
  Poland (1772)** — confirming its diminished weight

---

## The Napoleonic Wars: Strategic Stalemate and British Victory

### The Whale vs. the Elephant

- Core strategic dilemma of 1793–1815: Britain supreme at sea,
  France supreme on land — neither could deliver a knockout blow
- British sea control couldn't destroy French hegemony in Europe;
  Napoleon's land mastery couldn't force Britain to surrender
- French territorial resentment kept continental powers from
  permanently accepting French primacy — as long as Britain
  remained independent and offered subsidies, alliances could form
- Napoleon (1797): "Let us concentrate our efforts on building up
  our fleet and on destroying England. Once that is done Europe
  is at our feet."
- Yet French naval strategy was required to do what military
  gains on land could not — and Britain had to secure continental
  allies since Royal Navy mastery alone was insufficient

### Napoleon's Egypt Gambit and the Second Coalition (1798–1800)

- Napoleon's bold counter: invaded Egypt (1798) with 31,000 troops
  to dominate the Levant, Ottoman Empire, and route to India
- Simultaneous French expedition to Ireland as a distraction
- Both strokes failed: **Nelson** destroyed the French fleet at
  **Aboukir Bay**; Irish landing was contained by September 1798
- The naval defeat triggered the **Second Coalition** (1798–1800):
  Russia, Austria, Turkey, Portugal, Naples joined Britain
- Second Coalition structurally weak: Prussia absent (no northern
  German front), premature Neapolitan campaign ended in disaster,
  Anglo-Russian expedition to Holland failed to rouse locals
- Austria and Russia failed to cooperate in Switzerland;
  Russians driven east, Czar Paul grew suspicious of British motives
- Napoleon slipped back to France, crushed Austrians at
  **Marengo** and **Hochstadt** (June 1800), then **Hohenlinden** —
  forcing Vienna to sue for peace again
- Britain stood virtually alone by 1801; Russia, Denmark, Sweden,
  Prussia formed a new **Armed Neutrality League** to exclude
  British Baltic trade
- British maritime successes offset land failures: captured Malta,
  smashed the Danish fleet off **Copenhagen**, defeated French at
  **Alexandria**, ejected them from Egypt, seized French/Dutch/
  Danish colonies in West Indies and India

### Peace of Amiens (1802) and Its Breakdown

- Exhaustion on both sides + Pitt's resignation led to negotiations
- Napoleon's logic for peace: consolidate French satellite states,
  rebuild dispersed navy, rest the economy before next round
- **Peace of Amiens** (March 1802) initially accepted by British
  opinion — but sentiment swung as France continued expanding by
  other means: denied British trade access across Europe, French
  warship-building program accelerated, intrigues from Muscat to
  Piedmont
- Britain refused to return Malta; **May 1803** the cold war
  turned hot — beginning the final and most severe of the seven
  Anglo-French wars (1689–1815)

### The Final Round: 1803–1815

- Royal Navy immediately recaptured French/satellite overseas
  empire systematically: St. Lucia, Tobago, Dutch Guiana (pre-
  Trafalgar); Cape of Good Hope (1806); Curaçao, Danish West
  Indies (1807); Moluccas (1808); Cayenne, Martinique, Senegal
  (1809); Guadeloupe, Mauritius, Java (1810–1811)
- These seizures provided Britain new export markets and denied
  France shipbuilding timber and colonial revenue
- Grand Army assembled at Boulogne for invasion; **Pitt** returned
  to office 1804; both sides expected a decisive clash
- French navy ~70 ships of the line + Spanish reinforcement (~20+),
  but dispersed across six harbors — junction impossible without
  facing the battle-hardened Royal Navy
- **Battle of Trafalgar** (October 1805): Franco-Spanish fleet
  annihilated — settled British naval supremacy permanently, but
  could not dislodge Napoleon from the continent
- Even before Trafalgar, Napoleon had rushed army from Boulogne,
  destroyed Austrians at **Ulm**, crushed Austro-Russian force of
  85,000 at **Austerlitz** (December 1805) — Vienna sued for peace
  a third time

### Napoleon at His Zenith, 1806–1807

- **Prussia** rashly declared war October 1806 — crushed within
  the month at **Jena**
- Russia held out longer but badly hurt at **Friedland** (June 1807)
- **Treaties of Tilsit** (1807): Prussia made virtual satellite;
  Russia agreed to ban British trade and join French alliance
- By 1807: no independent state between Portugal and Sweden;
  **Holy Roman Empire** abolished; **Confederation of the Rhine**
  created from western/southern Germany; western Poland became
  **Grand Duchy of Warsaw**; Spain, Italy, Low Countries subservient
- Kennedy's map (Map 7): "Europe at the Height of Napoleon's Power,
  1810" — French Empire + "Greater Empire" + nominal allies cover
  nearly all of continental Europe

### The Continental System: Economic Warfare

- Napoleon's **Berlin/Milan Decrees** (1806–1807): banned all
  British trade with Europe — the **Continental System**
- Britain's vulnerability: large dependence on foreign commerce;
  1808 and 1811–1812 crises piled up manufactured goods in
  warehouses, London docks overflowed, unemployment rose,
  national debt soared
- Yet the Continental System never applied consistently enough to
  take full effect:
  - Spain's revolt against French hegemony (1808) broke the
    blockade, easing the 1808 crisis
  - Russia's break with Napoleon (December 1810) relieved 1811–
    1812 slump, opening Baltic and northern Europe to British goods
  - Massive smuggling from Heligoland to Salonika — banned goods
    traveled circuitous routes to eager customers with bribed
    local officials
  - New markets untouched by Continental System: Asia, Africa,
    West Indies, Latin America, Near East
- British total exports: £21.7M (1794–96) → £37.5M (1804–06)
  → £44.4M (1814–16) — *rising throughout the war overall*

### Britain's Industrial Revolution as a Strategic Asset

- The other reason Britain didn't crumble: it was now deep into
  the **Industrial Revolution** — which Napoleon could not match
- War spending (estimated at 29% of GNP) stimulated iron, steel,
  coal, timber; armament orders boosted iron industry; new export
  markets compensated for French blockade
- **Pig-iron output**: 68,000 tons (1788) → 244,000 tons (1806)
  → 325,000 tons (1811)
- **Cotton**: virtually a new industry before the war; by 1815
  Britain's *greatest export* — absorbed ever more steam power,
  machinery, coal, labor
- New canals, turnpikes, iron rail tracks improved communications
  and stimulated production
- British fiscal capacity expanded with its economy:
  - Customs/excise: £13.5M (1793) → £44.8M (1815)
  - Income/property taxes: £1.67M (1799) → £14.6M (1815)
  - 1793–1815 total from direct + indirect taxes: **£1.217 billion**
  - Additional **£440 million** raised in loans without exhausting
    credit — to Napoleon's fiscal amazement
  - Final years of war: borrowing >£25M annually, providing
    decisive margin for subsidies and expeditionary forces
- Key insight: new industrial wealth made higher taxes bearable —
  Britain, despite smaller population, outlasted the Napoleonic
  Empire financially

### France's Economy: Relative Weakness

- French economy grew, but much more slowly than Britain's
- Agriculture (the largest sector) barely changed; replacing the
  seigneur with peasants was *not* an agricultural revolution
- Poor communications tied farmers to local markets; little
  stimulus for radical innovation
- Industrial sector: new machinery and large-scale enterprises
  were the exception, not the rule
- French cotton industry benefited from Continental System
  (protected from British competition), and Napoleon's conquests
  expanded the "French" domestic market from 25M (1789) to 44M
  (1810) — but offset by shortage and high price of raw cotton
- Naval blockade cut off France's Atlantic sector (fastest-growing
  in the 18th century): Bordeaux devastated, Nantes' slave trade
  reduced to nothing, Marseilles' output fell to one-quarter by 1813
- France turned inward — deindustrialized in its Atlantic sector,
  reliant on peasants, smalltown commerce, localized industries
- French industry emerged from the war in a *less competitive*
  state due to protection from foreign rivals

### Napoleon's War Finance: Plunder

- Normal French revenues couldn't fund the war: military
  expenditure 462M francs (1807) → 817M francs (1813)
- Direct taxes politically impossible to raise substantially —
  Napoleon returned to *ancien régime* indirect taxes (tobacco,
  salt), created the **Bank of France** for disguised paper money
- The fiscal gap was filled by the **domaine extraordinaire** —
  systematic plunder:
  - Confiscation of crown and feudal properties in conquered lands
  - Spoils from enemy armies, garrisons, museums, treasuries
  - War indemnities in money and in kind
  - Satellite states required to quarter French regiments and
    supply military contingents
- Prussia paid 311M francs after Jena (= half of France's ordinary
  annual revenue); Habsburg Empire ceded territory *and* paid
  indemnity at each defeat; in Italy 1805–1812, about half of all
  taxes raised went to France
- "War would support war" — kept the army *outside* France,
  sparing French taxpayers; system seemed invulnerable as long as
  Napoleon kept winning

> "My power depends on my glory and my glories on the victories I
> have won. My power will fail if I do not feed it on new glories
> and new victories. Conquest has made me what I am and only
> conquest can enable me to hold my position."
> — *Napoleon*

### The Structural Contradiction of Napoleon's Empire

- A nation proclaiming liberty, fraternity, equality was
  conquering non-French populations, taxing them, conscripting
  their youth, distorting their trade — breeding resentment
- Continental System hurt not only Nantes and Bordeaux but also
  Amsterdam, Hamburg, and Trieste
- Few openly revolted (the Spanish did; the Russians quit in
  December 1810) — but the system depended on unbroken military
  success

### The Peninsular War: Napoleon's "Spanish Ulcer"

- Napoleon's invasion of Spain (late 1808) dispersed formal
  Spanish armies but inadvertently triggered **guerrilla warfare** —
  far harder to suppress, multiplied logistical problems
- French army critically dependent on supply lines denied food by
  hostile local population
- Spain/Portugal = one of the few terrains where Britain *would*
  commit a substantial land army: **Wellington** exploited local
  sympathies, geography of the peninsula, and command of the sea
- 25,000 casualties in Massena's fruitless march against Lisbon
  (1810–1811) showed the "Spanish ulcer" couldn't be lanced even
  with 300,000 French troops south of the Pyrenees
- Strategic double effect: weakened France *and* relieved Britain
  — Spain now allied with Britain rather than adding Franco-Spanish
  naval threat
- British exports soared to record **£48M in 1810** (from £37M
  in 1808) as Lancashire and Midlands goods returned to Iberian
  and Latin American markets

### The Russian Campaign and Collapse (1812)

- French overstretch by 1811: 353,000 troops in Spain, as
  Wellington observed, "had no authority beyond the spot where
  they stood" — a mere 27,000 could be withdrawn to join the
  Russian march
- Grand Army for Russia: >600,000 men, of whom only 270,000 were
  French — and "native Frenchmen" now included Belgians, Dutch,
  many Italians; troops from pre-1789 France were a decided minority
- Casualties in the Russian campaign: ~270,000 killed, 200,000
  captured, ~1,000 guns and 200,000 horses lost
- Russia's army had little capacity to pursue aggressively into
  Germany; Napoleon raised 145,000 fresh troops by summer 1813,
  held Saxony, negotiated armistice
- **Wellington's victory at Vitoria** (June 1813) drove Joseph
  Bonaparte's army to the Pyrenees — critically encouraged Austria
  to declare war and combine with Russia, Prussia, Sweden
- **Battle of Leipzig** ("Battle of Nations," October 1813):
  195,000 French overwhelmed in four days by 365,000 allied troops,
  economically underpinned by British subsidies + 125,000 muskets,
  218 artillery pieces, and equipment from Britain
- Napoleon conducted brilliant tactical defense of northeastern
  France early 1814, but army was drained with too many raw
  recruits; French populace unenthusiastic once fighting reached
  home soil
- **March 30, 1814**: allied forces entered Paris; within a week
  Napoleon had abdicated

### The Vienna Settlement (1815) and Britain's Post-War Supremacy

- Vienna settlement did not partition France; instead surrounded
  it with strong buffer states: Kingdom of the Netherlands,
  enlarged Kingdom of Sardinia (Piedmont), Prussia in the Rhineland
- Principles of **"containment and reciprocal compensation"** —
  no power could unilaterally dominate; even small territorial
  changes required majority Concert approval
- Russian demands over Poland checked by Anglo-French-Austrian
  threat; Prussia didn't get Saxony, accepted Posen and Rhineland
- Napoleon's final campaign (**Waterloo**, June 1815) a strategic
  footnote — even without defeat, France couldn't economically
  sustain prolonged war against reconstituted coalition
- **Waterloo's political significance**: reinforced need for French
  buffer states, demonstrated Prussia's military recovery,
  compelled all Vienna powers to bury remaining differences
- Post-1815 balance: rough parity on land among five Great Powers,
  but Britain held near-**monopoly of naval power** — reinforced
  by and underpinning its economic lead
- Britain's overseas acquisitions (India, West Indies, the Cape,
  etc.) plus maritime routes and re-export trades = richest nation
  in per capita terms by 1815
- Kutusov (Russian general, 1812), wary of totally destroying
  Napoleon: "the succession would not fall to Russia or to any
  other continental power, but to the power which already commands
  the sea, and whose domination would be intolerable"

> "Great Britain has no greater obligation than to this ruffian
> [Napoleon]. For through the events which he has brought about,
> England's greatness, prosperity, and wealth have risen high. She
> is mistress of the sea and neither in this dominion nor in world
> trade has she now a single rival to fear."
> — *Gneisenau* (Prussian general)

- The **equilibrium of power** that Pitt and Castlereagh championed
  applied only to European territorial arrangements — not to the
  colonial and commercial spheres, where Britain faced no
  equivalent constraint
- Britain would go on to become the "**superdominant economy**"
  in the world's trading structure in the following half-century

---

*[New section begins: "Strategy & Economics in the Industrial Era"]*

<!-- pp. 201-220 -->

## Chapter 4: Industrialization and the Shifting Global Balances, 1815–1885

### Overview: The Post-Napoleonic International System

- The half-century after Napoleon's fall produced an unusual cluster of
  features — some temporary, some permanent fixtures of modernity
- **First feature:** Steady then spectacular growth of an integrated
  **global economy** centered on western Europe (especially Britain),
  drawing regions into a transoceanic financial and trading network
- **Second feature:** No prolonged Great Power wars — but colonial wars
  of conquest against less-developed peoples *intensified*, functioning
  as the military concomitant to economic penetration
  - Regional European conflicts (Franco-Austrian War 1859, German
    unification wars 1860s, Crimean War) were limited in duration
  - Only the **American Civil War** was a true exception
- **Third feature:** Industrial Revolution technology began reshaping
  military and naval power — but slowly; only in the second half of
  the century did railways, telegraphs, quick-firing guns, steam
  propulsion, and armored warships become decisive
- **Key caveat on war finance:** Mid-19th-century wars were short enough
  that industrial/technological superiority mattered more than finance;
  no amount of money could have saved Austria after Sadowa (1866) or
  France after Sedan (1870) once battlefield defeat occurred
  - Finance *did* help the North beat the South, and Britain/France
    over Russia in Crimea — but mainly because it reflected overall
    economic superiority, not finance alone

### The Industrial Revolution: Nature and Impact

- The **Industrial Revolution** was gradual, not overnight — unlike
  political revolutions of 1776, 1789, or 1917; it affected only
  certain manufactures and occurred region by region
- Core transformation: substitution of **inanimate for animate sources
  of power** — heat converted into work through machines described as
  "rapid, regular, precise, tireless" (**Professor Landes**)
- Scale of productivity leap:
  - By the 1820s, power-driven looms produced 20× the output of a
    hand worker
  - A power-driven "mule" (spinning machine) had 200× the capacity
    of a spinning wheel
  - A single railway engine replaced hundreds of packhorses
- Productivity gains were **self-sustaining** — unlike all previous
  economic improvements which were ultimately consumed by population
  growth (**Malthus's positive checks**):

> "Where previously an amelioration of the conditions of existence… had
> always been followed by a rise in population that eventually consumed
> the gains achieved, now for the first time in history, both the economy
> and the knowledge were growing fast enough to generate a continuing flow
> of investment and technological innovation, a flow that lifted beyond
> visible limits the ceiling of Malthus's positive checks."
> — *Professor Landes*

### Population Growth vs. Productivity

- World population surged from the 18th century onward:
  - Europe: 140M (1750) → 187M (1800) → 266M (1850)
  - Asia: 400M+ (1750) → ~700M a century later
- In pre-industrial societies, population growth cancelled productivity
  gains; in Britain, industrialization outpaced demographics:
  - UK population: 10.5M (1801) → 41.8M (1911) — 1.26% annual growth
  - National product rose ~14×; per capita GNP grew 2–2.25%/year
  - In Queen Victoria's reign alone, product per capita rose **2.5×**
- Real wages in Britain: +15–25% in 1815–1850; +80% in the next
  50 years
- **Ashton's counterpoint** to critics of industrialization:

> "The central problem of the age was how to feed and clothe and employ
> generations of children outnumbering by far those of any earlier time."
> — *Ashton*

- **Landes's energy calculation:** In 1870, UK used 100M tons of coal
  — equivalent to 800 million million Calories, enough to feed 850M
  adult males; its 4M horsepower of steam engines equaled the power
  of 40M men, who would have consumed 320M bushels of wheat per year
  — more than 3× the UK's entire annual output in 1867–71
- Contrast: without an industrial revolution, population growth leads
  only to grinding poverty — as **Ashton** observed of India and China
  in 1947:

> "There are today on the plains of India and China men and women,
> plague-ridden and hungry, living lives little better, to outward
> appearance, than those of the cattle that toil with them by day…
> Such Asiatic standards… are the lot of those who increase their
> numbers without passing through an industrial revolution."
> — *Ashton*

### The Eclipse of the Non-European World

- Non-European losses were **twofold — relative and absolute**
- Myth debunked: pre-industrial Asian/African/Latin American life was
  not a "happy, ideal existence" — poverty and low surplus were the
  norm in any pre-industrial agricultural economy
- Around 1800, per capita income gaps were not enormous: an Indian
  handloom weaver may have earned ~half his European equivalent
- Asia's *total* manufacturing share was large due to sheer population
  — China and India dominated world output when output was measured
  simply by numbers of workers and looms

