### Scholarly Patterns Worth Noting
- Kennedy consistently cites **conflicting** figures rather
  than selecting one — signals awareness of data fragility
- Heavy reliance on **McKay & Scott**, *Rise of the Great
  Powers* as a general-purpose reference across chapters
- **Mahan** (*Influence of Sea Power upon History*) cited
  repeatedly — Kennedy engages Mahan's thesis throughout
  the early modern chapters
- **Crouzet** is the go-to source for Britain-France
  economic comparisons across multiple chapters
- Self-citation of *Rise and Fall of British Naval Mastery*
  for naval data — Kennedy building on his own prior work

