## Footnotes Section

### Footnote 190 — Soviet Conventional Military Capability in Europe

- **Footnote 190** addresses a "tricky (and highly disputed) topic" — the question of Soviet conventional military strength relative to NATO
- Kennedy notes he sides with the **optimists' view** that the Soviets could not achieve rapid conventional victory in Central Europe

**Key sources cited (optimist/skeptical of Soviet superiority):**
- **J. Mearsheimer**, "Why the Soviets Can't Win Quickly in Central Europe," pp. 121–57, in Miller (ed.), *Conventional Forces and American Defense Policy*
- **B. R. Posen**, "Measuring the European Conventional Balance," pp. 79–120, same volume
- **Steele**, *Soviet Power*, pp. 76ff
- **C. N. Donnelly**, "Tactical Problems Facing the Soviet Army: Recent Debates in the Soviet Military Press," *International Defense Review*, vol. 11, no. 9 (1978), pp. 1405–12

**More sobering (less optimistic) assessments:**
- **R. A. Mason**, "Military Strategy," in Moreton & Segal (eds.), *Soviet Strategy Toward Western Europe* (London, 1984), pp. 175–202
- **P. A. Peterson & J. G. Hines**, "The Conventional Offensive in Soviet Theater Strategy," *Orbis*, vol. 27, no. 3 (Fall 1983), pp. 695–739
- **D. M. Gormley**, "A New Dimension to Soviet Theater Strategy," *Orbis*, vol. 29, no. 3 (Fall 1985), pp. 537–69 — raises concern about Soviet use of **dual-purpose (tactical nuclear) missiles**

*Note: Page ends mid-footnote; continues on next page.*

